The function  	\( f(x) = $a x \ln(1 + x) \) is represented as a power series   	\( \displaystyle f(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty c_n x^n .\)  Find the FOLLOWING coefficients in the power series.   \( c_2 = \) \{ans_rule(20)\}   \( c_3 = \) \{ans_rule(20)\}   \( c_4 = \) \{ans_rule(20)\}   \( c_5 = \) \{ans_rule(20)\}   \( c_6 = \) \{ans_rule(20)\}    Find the radius of convergence \( R \) of the series.   \( R = \)  \{ans_rule(20)\}  .   END_TEXT  #@ans=(); $ans0 =  $a/1; $ans1 =  -1*$a/2; $ans2 =  $a/3; $ans3 =  -1*$a/4; $ans4 =  $a/5; $ans5 =  1;  #ANS(num_cmp(relTol=>@ans)); #ANS(ordered_num_cmp_list(@ans) ); ANS(num_cmp($ans0)); ANS(num_cmp($ans1)); ANS(num_cmp($ans2)); ANS(num_cmp($ans3)); ANS(num_cmp($ans4)); ANS(num_cmp($ans5));  &SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $SOL      Since \( \displaystyle \ln(1-x) = - \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{x^n}n \) by example ${pound}6 on p.748, we also therefore have \( \displaystyle \ln(1+x) = - \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-x)^n}n \). Thus \[ \begin{aligned} $a x \ln(1+x) &=	-$a \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-x)^n x}n	\\\\ &=	$a \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-x)^{n+1}}n	\\\\ &=	\frac{$a x^2}1 - \frac{$a x^3}2 + \frac{$a x^4}3 - \cdots \end{aligned} \] and so  \( c_0 = 0 \), \( c_1 = 0 \), \( c_2 = $a \), \( c_3 = \frac{-$a}2 = $ans1 \), \( c_4 = \frac{$a}3 = $ans2 \), and in general, \( c_n = \frac{$a(-1)^n}{n-1} \) for all \( n \geq 2 \).
keywords_in_text: ['power function', 'series', 'radius', 'power series radius of convergence', 'power', 'power series convergence', 'radius of convergence', 'power series', 'function', 'convergence']

The effects of scaling, explored in the previous two problems for cubes and spheres, also apply to odd shaped objects.  Just think of them as composed of many small cubes and ask what happens to the cubes as you change their lengths.     In the novel $BITALIC Gulliver's travels $EITALIC by Jonathan Swift,  Gulliver visits a country, $BITALIC Brobdingnag $EITALIC , in which everything,  including people, plants, buildings, etc., is 12 times as large as in England. (In that same novel Gulliver visits several other strange countries, and in a conversation with the King of Brobdingnag casually refers to the future United States as "our plantations in America".)  Suppose Gulliver encounters a giant who is shaped exactly like Gulliver, except he is twelve times as tall.  Then the weight of that giant is \{ ans_rule(10) \} times that of Gulliver. EOT ANS(num_cmp(12**3)); TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); The area of the cross section of one of the giant's bones is   \{ ans_rule(10) \} times that of Gulliver's corresponding bone. EOT ANS(num_cmp(12**2)); TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); Hence the ratio of the giant's weight and the area of his bone's cross section is \{ ans_rule(10) \} times that of Gulliver's corresponding ratio.  What do you think would happen to the giant?   EOT ANS(num_cmp(12));      TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  Hint: Understand \{htmlLink("http://www.math.utah.edu/online/1010/scale/", "scaling")\}. EOT   SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD Those giants would weigh \(12^3=1728\) times as much as ordinary human beings, but the cross section of their bones would be multiplied only with \(12^2=144\).  As a result the giants would be sprawling on the ground unable to move.  They would also suffocate because their need of oxygen is multiplied with 1728 but the inner surface of their lungs is multiplied only with 144.  If they could overcome those obstacles they would have to spend twelve times as much time as human beings ingesting food since their need for food is increased by a factor 1728, but the cross section of their esophagus, which determines their capacity to ingest food, only by 144.  If they could manage that they would still develop 1728 times as much heat, but they could shed it only through a surface that is 144 times as large as ours. So if they somehow did come to exist they would develop a fever and soon die.  Remarkably, this simple and compelling piece of mathematics and common sense did not stop Jonathan Swift from writing an entertaining and quite famous story!

Determine the sum of the following series.  \[ \sum_{n=1}^\infty \left( \sin \left( \frac{$a}{n} \right) -\sin \left( \frac{$a}{n+1}\right)\right) \] \{ans_rule(20)\} END_TEXT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOF')); $SOL  A partial sum is    \( \displaystyle s_n =  \left(\sin\left(\frac{$a}{1}\right)-\sin\left(\frac{$a}{2}\right)\right) +  \left(\sin\left(\frac{$a}{2}\right)-\sin\left(\frac{$a}{3}\right)\right) + \left(\sin\left(\frac{$a}{3}\right)-\sin\left(\frac{$a}{4}\right)\right) + ... +  \left(\sin\left(\frac{$a}{n-1}\right)-\sin\left(\frac{$a}{n}\right)\right) + \left(\sin\left(\frac{$a}{n}\right)-\sin\left(\frac{$a}{n+1}\right)\right) =  \sin\left(\frac{$a}{1}\right)- \sin\left(\frac{$a}{n+1}\right) = \sin($a) -  \sin\left(\frac{$a}{n+1}\right)\).    \( \displaystyle \lim_{n\to\infty} s_n =  \lim_{n\to\infty} \left(  \sin($a)- \sin\left(\frac{$a}{n+1}\right) \right) =  \sin($a)\).  Therefore the sum of the series is \( \sin($a) \).

question_text: Suppose the angle \( \theta \) is in the first quadrant, \( 0 \leq \theta \leq \pi /2 \), and \( \displaystyle \cos(\theta) = \frac{1}{$r} \).  Find exact values (as fractions, not decimal approximations) for the following.   (a)  \( \csc(\theta) \) = \{ ans_rule(20) \} \{ AnswerFormatHelp("fractions") \}   (b)  \( \cot(\theta) \) = \{ ans_rule(20) \} \{ AnswerFormatHelp("fractions") \} END_TEXT Context()->normalStrings;  ANS( $answercsc->cmp() ); ANS( $answercot->cmp() );   Context()->texStrings; SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));  $SPACE   $BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD   (a) Since \( \csc{ ( \theta ) } = \frac{1}{\sin{ ( \theta )}} \), we begin by using the Pythagorean Identity to find \( \sin{ ( \theta ) } \).  Since \( \cos^2{ ( \theta )} + \sin^2{ ( \theta ) }=1 \), we have  \[ \begin{array}{rcl}  \left( \frac{1}{$r} \right)^2 + \sin^2{ ( \theta ) } & = & 1  \\[1ex]  \sin^2{ ( \theta )} & = & 1 - \frac{1}{$sqr}  \\[1ex]  \sin{ ( \theta ) } & = & \pm \sqrt{ \frac{$disp}{$sqr} }. \end{array} \]   Since \( 0 \le \theta \le \frac{\pi}{2} \), \( \sin{ ( \theta ) } \ge 0 \), so \( \sin{ ( \theta ) } = \sqrt{ \frac{$disp}{$sqr}} \).  Thus, \( \csc{ ( \theta )} = \sqrt{ \frac{$sqr}{$disp}} \).     (b) Since \( \cot{ ( \theta ) }= \frac{ \cos{ ( \theta ) }}{\sin{ ( \theta ) }} \), we have \( \cot{ ( \theta ) } = \frac{1/$r}{\sqrt{$disp/$sqr}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{$disp}} \).

(I.e. use \( \displaystyle \int_{$d}^{\infty} f(x)dx \geq r_{$d} \)) 	\{ans_rule(20)\}  \( (c) \) Use n = $d and \[ s_n + \int_{n+1}^{\infty} f(x)dx \leq s \leq s_n + \int_{n}^{\infty}f(x)dx \] 	to find a better estimate of the sum.  	\{ans_rule(20)\} \( \leq s \leq \)  \{ans_rule(20)\} END_TEXT  # a simple code to perform a summation. (for A) 	$i = 1; 	$sum = 0; 	while ($i <= $d ) {                 $fofi = $a/($b*$i**$c); 		$sum = $sum + $fofi; 		$i = $i +1 ; 	} #to make sure that the answer is always an integer (for D) #	$terms =  (1/(3*$accuracy))**(1/3); #	if ($terms != int($terms)) { #		$terms = $terms +1 ; #		} #@ans=(); $ans0 = $sum ; $ans1 = $a/($b*$c1*$d**$c1); $ans2 = $sum + $a/($b*$c1*($d+1)**$c1); $ans3 = $sum + $a/($b*$c1*$d**$c1);  #ANS(num_cmp(relTol=>@ans)); #ANS(ordered_num_cmp_list(@ans) ); ANS(num_cmp($ans0)); ANS(num_cmp($ans1)); ANS(num_cmp($ans2)); ANS(num_cmp($ans3));  $soln_expand_a1 = ''; $soln_expand_a2 = ''; for $i (1..$d) { 	$soln_expand_a1 .= '+ \frac{'.$a.'}{'.$b.' \cdot '.$i.'^{'.$c.'}}'; 	$soln_pieces_a2 .= '+ '.($a/($b*($i**$c))); } $soln_expand_a1 = substr($soln_expand_a1,2); $soln_pieces_a2 = substr($soln_pieces_a2,2);  $soln_1mc = 1 - $c; $soln_cm1 = $c - 1; $soln_dt1mc = $d**$soln_1mc; $soln_bfrac = $a/($b*$soln_1mc); $soln_bfin = -$soln_bfrac*$soln_dt1mc;  $soln_c_right = $ans0 + $soln_bfin; $soln_dp1 = $d + 1; $soln_c_left_pre = $soln_dp1**$soln_1mc; $soln_c_left_fin = -$soln_bfrac*$soln_c_left_pre; $soln_c_left = $ans0 + $soln_c_left_fin;  &SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  For part (a), we simply compute: \[ \begin{aligned} s_d &=	\sum_{n=1}^{$d} \frac{$a}{$b \cdot n^{$c}}	\\\\ &=	$soln_expand_a1	\\\\ &=	$soln_pieces_a2	\\\\ &=	$ans0 \end{aligned} \]  For part (b), we simply evaluate the integral they asked us to evaluate: \[ \begin{aligned} \int_{$d}^\infty f(x) dx &=	\int_{$d}^\infty \frac{$a}{$b \cdot x^{$c}} dx	\\\\ &=	\frac{$a}{$b} \int_{$d}^\infty x^{-$c} dx	\\\\ &=	\frac{$a}{$b} 		\left \left(\frac{x^{-$c+1}}{-$c+1}\right)\right|_{$d}^\infty	\\\\ &=	\frac{$a}{$b($soln_1mc)} 		\left( \lim_{n\to\infty} \frac{1}{x^{$soln_cm1}} - 			\frac{1}{$d^{$soln_cm1}} \right)	\\\\ &=	$soln_bfrac \left( 0 - $soln_dt1mc \right) = $soln_bfin \end{aligned} \]  For part (c), we are asked to compute \[ s_n + \int_{n+1}^{\infty} f(x)dx \leq s \leq s_n + \int_{n}^{\infty}f(x)dx \] but conveniently enough, we've already calculated both \(s_$d\) and the right hand integral, \(\displaystyle \int_{$d}^\infty} f(x) dx \).  So about half our work is done: \[ \begin{aligned} s_n + \int_{n}^\infty f(x) dx &=	s_{$d} + \int_{$d}^\infty f(x) dx	\\\\ &=	$ans0 + $soln_bfin	\\\\ &=	$soln_c_right \end{aligned} \] Now for the left hand side, we must simply calculate \( \displaystyle \int_{n+1}^\infty f(x) dx = \int_{$d+1}^\infty f(x) dx 	= \int_{$soln_dp1}^\infty f(x) dx \), but if we examine our work above, we need not re-integrate everything, we can simply evaluate \( $soln_bfrac \left( 0 - \frac{1}{$soln_dp1^{$soln_cm1}} \right) 	= $soln_bfrac(-$soln_c_left_pre) = $soln_c_left_fin \). Thus we have \[ \begin{aligned} s_n + \int_{n+1}^\infty f(x) dx &=	s_{$soln_dp1} + \int_{$soln_dp1}^\infty f(x) dx	\\\\ &=	$ans0 + $soln_c_left_fin	\\\\ &=	$soln_c_left \end{aligned} \] So the estimate of \(s\) becomes this good:   \[ $soln_c_left \leq s \leq $soln_c_right \]

Note that \( r = $r \) is the radius of the circle, and \( s = $s \) is the arc length from the point \( ($r,0) \) around the circle to the indicated point.". . . "\( p = \) ".ans_rule(30).$SPACE.AnswerFormatHelp("numbers"), $fig. .$BCENTER."(Click on graph to enlarge)".$ECENTER, indent => 0, separation => 30, valign => "TOP" ) \} END_TEXT Context()->normalStrings;   ANS($answera->cmp(tolerance=>0.00000001,tolType=>"absolute") ); ANS($answerb->cmp(tolerance=>0.00000001,tolType=>"absolute") ); ANS($answerc->cmp(tolerance=>0.00000001,tolType=>"absolute") );  #ANS(num_cmp( $m, tol=>0.00000000000001 ) ); #ANS(num_cmp( $n, tol=>0.00000000000001 ) ); #ANS(num_cmp( $p, tol=>0.00000000000001 ) );   $dbl = 2*$r; $sqr = $r**2; $dbl_sqr = 2*$sqr;  Context()->texStrings; SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR $BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD $PAR The angle spanned by the arc shown is \( \theta = s/r = \frac{$s}{$r} \) radians, so \( a = r \cos{ \theta }= $r \cos{ ($s / $r)} \) and \( b = r \sin{ \theta} = $r \sin{($s / $r)}\).  By the Pythagorean theorem, $PAR \( \begin{array}{rl} p^2 &= b^2 + ($r - a)^2 \\ &= b^2 + a^2 - $dbl a + $sqr \\ &= $sqr \sin^2{($s/$r)} + $sqr \cos^2{($s/$r)} - $dbl a + $sqr \\ &= $dbl_sqr - $dbl a \end{array} \) $PAR so  \( \begin{array}{rl} p &= \sqrt{$dbl_sqr - $dbl a} \\ &= \sqrt{$dbl_sqr - $dbl_sqr \cos{($s / $r)}} \\ &= $r \sqrt{2 (1 - \cos{ ($s / $r)})} \end{array} \)

Before calculators were widely available people used logarithm tables to simplify multiplication and division, using the fact that the logarithm of a product equals the sum of the logarithms and the logarithm of the quotient equals the difference of the logarithms.    These tables were constructed by computing laboriously and carefully the logarithms of a few selected numbers and then combining the logarithms using the rules just mentioned.   This exercise suggest how the process may have worked.    Let  \[L(x) = \hbox{log}_a(x)\] where we don't know the base \(a\).  However, we do know that   \[L(2) = $a \quad\hbox{and}\quad L(3) = $b.\]   Use this information to compute     \(L(6)= \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}. EOT ANS(num_cmp($a+$b, mode=>"strict"));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));   \(L(9) = \)    \{ ans_rule(20) \}. EOT ANS(num_cmp(2*$b, mode=>"strict"));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));   \(L(12) = \)    \{ ans_rule(20) \}. EOT ANS(num_cmp(2*$a+$b, mode=>"strict"));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));   \(L\left(\frac{2}{3}\right) = \)    \{ ans_rule(20) \}. EOT ANS(num_cmp($a-$b, mode=>"strict"));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));   \(L\left(3^{10}\right) = \)    \{ ans_rule(20) \}. EOT ANS(num_cmp(10*$b, mode=>"strict"));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));   \(L(1) = \)    \{ ans_rule(20) \}.  EOT ANS(num_cmp(0, mode=>"strict"));    $a1=int(100000*($a+$b))/100000; $a2=int(100000*($b+$b))/100000; $a3=int(100000*(2*$a+$b))/100000; $a4=int(100000*($a-$b))/100000; $a5=int(100000*(10*$b))/100000;   SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));   $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD  Using the rules mentioned in the problem we obtain \[\begin{array}{rcccl} L(6) &=& L(2)+L(3) &\approx& $a1 \\ L(9) &=& L(3)+L(3) &\approx& $a2 \\ L(12) &=& 2L(2)+L(3) &\approx& $a3 \\ L\left(\frac{2}{3}\right) ) &=& L(2)-L(3) &\approx& $a4 \\ L\left(3^{10}\right) &=& 10L(3) &\approx& $a5 \\ \end{array} \]  Of course, the logarithm of \(1\) with any base is zero.

The smallest positive number for which \[\sin(x+1) = \sin (x) \] is \(x=\)  \{ans_rule(12) \}. EOT $pi=2.0*acos(0.0); ANS(num_cmp(($pi-1)/2));  TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Hint:$EBOLD Look at the graph of the sin function and exploit symmetry. EOT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));   $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD Our equation can be rewritten as \[\sin(x+1) - \sin x = 0.\] Applying the formula \[\sin u - \sin v = 2\cos\frac{u+v}{2}\sin\frac{u-v}{2}\] this turns into \[2\cos\frac{2x+1}{2}\sin\frac{1}{2} = 0 .\] Thus we have to solve the equation \[\cos \frac{2x+1}{2}= 0 \] The smallest positive solution of that equation is obtained by solving  \[\frac{2x+1}{2} = \frac{\pi}{2}\] giving \[x= \frac{\pi-1}{2} \approx 1.071.\]

If not, determine a domain on which \($map\) is one-to-one. $PAR Find the image under \($map\) of: $PAR \{$checkbox_mc1->print_q\}  \{$checkbox_mc1->print_a\} $PAR \{$checkbox_mc2->print_q\}  \{$checkbox_mc2->print_a\} $PAR \{$checkbox_mc3->print_q\}  \{$checkbox_mc3->print_a\} $PAR \{$checkbox_mc4->print_q\}  \{$checkbox_mc4->print_a\} $PAR  END_TEXT  ANS(str_cmp($checkbox_mc1->correct_ans)); ANS(str_cmp($checkbox_mc2->correct_ans)); ANS(str_cmp($checkbox_mc3->correct_ans)); ANS(str_cmp($checkbox_mc4->correct_ans));  Context()->texStrings;  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR $SOL \(\Phi\) is not one-to-one since for any \(u\ne 0\), \(( u,v )\) and \(( -u,v )\) are two different points with the same image.  However,  \(\Phi\) is one-to-one on the domain \( \lbrace ( u,v ): u\ge 0 \rbrace\} \) and on the domain \(\lbrace ( u,v ): u\le 0\rbrace\). $PAR \((\mathbf{a})\) The image of the \(u\)-axis is the set of the points \[( x,y )=\Phi ( u,0 )=({u}^2,0)\quad\Rightarrow\quad x={u}^2,\quad y=0\]  That is, the positive \(x\)-axis, including the origin.  The image of the \(v\)-axis is the set of the following points: \[( x,y )=\Phi ( 0,v )=({0}^2,v)=( 0,v )\quad\Rightarrow\quad x=0,\quad y=v\] That is, the line \(x=0\), which is the \(y\)-axis. $PAR \((\mathbf{b})\) The rectangle \(\mathcal{R}\) is defined by \[|u|\le $r,\quad |v|\le $r\] \{image("image_15_5_3_a.png", width=>209, height=>199)\} For \(r_0=$r\) $PAR Since \(x={u}^2\) and \(y=v\), we have \(u=\pm \sqrt{x}\) and \(v=y\) (depending on our choice of domain).  Therefore, the inequalities for \(x\) and \(y\) are \[ |\pm \sqrt{x}|\le $r,\quad |y|\le $r\]  or \[0\le x\le $r2\quad\text{and}\quad -$r\le y\le $r.\] We conclude that the image of \(\mathcal{R}\) in the \(xy\)-plane is the rectangle \([0,$r2]\times [-$r,$r]\).$PAR \{image("image_15_5_3_c.png", width=>142, height=>202)\} \(r_0=$r,\quad r_1=$r2\) $PAR \((\mathbf{c})\)The line segment joining the points \(( 0,0 )\) and \(( $a,$a )\) in the \(uv\)-plane is defined by \[0\le u\le $a,\quad v=u.\] Substituting \(u=\sqrt{x}\) and \(v=y\), we get \[ 0\le \sqrt{x}\le $a,\quad y=\sqrt{x} \]  or \[0\le x\le $a2,\quad y=\sqrt{x}\] $PAR \{ image(insertGraph($graph1uv), width=>300, height=>300) \} \(\quad \underrightarrow{\Phi}\quad\) \{ image(insertGraph($graph1xy), width=>300, height=>300) \}  The image is the curve \(y=\sqrt{x}\) for \(0\le x\le $a2\). $PAR \((\mathbf{d})\) We identify the image of the sides of the triangle \(OAB\).

(Note that the positive direction is down.)  $PAR Take as the gravitational acceleration 32 feet per second per second.    \(y= \) \{ans_box(2,80)\}  END_TEXT  HINT(EV3(<<'EOF')); When using English units (lb, ft, etc.) you need to be a bit careful with equations involving mass. This is causing some confusion --- I hope this hint helps: $PAR Pounds (lb) is a unit of force, not mass.  Using \( mg=F \) and \( g = 32\,\text{ft}/\text{sec}^2 \), we see that an object at the surface of the earth that weighs 32 lbs (i.e. the force on it is 32 lbs) will have a mass of 1 slug (the unit of mass in the English units is called the slug -- really!)  So one slug weighs 32 lbs at the surface of the earth (or \( 1\,\text{lb} = (1/32)\times\text{slug}\times\text{ft}/\text{sec}^2 \)). $PAR When using metric units, kilograms is a unit of mass, not force or weight. A 1-kilogram mass will weigh \( 1 \times 9.8 \) newtons on the surface of the earth. Convert to decimal degrees:  \($degrees[0]^{\circ} $minutes[0]' $seconds[0]''\) = \{ans_rule(30) \}\(^{\circ}\)  \($degrees[1]^{\circ} $minutes[1]' $seconds[1]''\) = \{ans_rule(30) \}\(^{\circ}\) $PAR Convert to degrees-minutes-seconds:  \($DD[2]^{\circ} \) =\{ans_rule(10) \}\(^{\circ}\) \{ans_rule(10) \}\('\) \{ans_rule(10) \}\(''\)  END_TEXT  &ANS(std_num_cmp($DD[0])); &ANS(std_num_cmp($DD[1])); &ANS(std_num_cmp($degrees[2])); &ANS(std_num_cmp($minutes[2])); &ANS(std_num_cmp($seconds[2]));   BEGIN_HINT $PAR One minute is equal to 60 seconds.   One degree is equal to 60 minutes. END_HINT  BEGIN_SOLUTION $PAR $BBOLD SOLUTION $EBOLD $PAR $BBOLD To convert to decimal degrees $EBOLD,   remember that  \(60'=1^{\circ}\).  Dividing both sides by 60 gives \[1' = (1/60)^{\circ}\]  Also, \(60''=1'\).  Multiply both sides by \(60\) so that  \(3600''=60'=1^{\circ}\).  Dividing by 3600 gives \[1''= (1/3600)^{\circ}\] So,   \($degrees[0]^{\circ} $minutes[0]' $seconds[0]''\)  = \($degrees[0]^{\circ} + $minutes[0]/60^{\circ} + $seconds[0]/3600^{\circ} = $DD[0]^{\circ}\)  \($degrees[1]^{\circ} $minutes[1]' $seconds[1]''\)  = \($degrees[1]^{\circ} + $minutes[1]/60^{\circ} + $seconds[1]/3600^{\circ} = $DD[1]^{\circ}\) $PAR $BBOLD To convert from decimal degrees back to degrees-minutes-seconds $EBOLD  consider a reverse procedure where you now multiply by 60s.   $PAR For \($DD[2]^{\circ} \), the whole number of degrees can be read off as \($degrees[2]^{\circ} \).    Subtracting this leaves the decimal part \($Ddeg2\). $PAR Multiply this result by 60 to convert to \($Dmin2\) minutes.    The whole number of minutes for this value is \($minutes[2]\).   $PAR Subtracting this leaves the decimal part \($Dsec2\).

For this problem use the \(\tan\) substitution. \[x = {$a}\tan(\theta)\] Before proceeding note that \(\tan\theta=\frac{x}{$a}\), and \(\sec\theta=\frac{\sqrt{$a2+x^2}}{$a}\). To see this, label a right triangle so that the tangent is \(x/$a\). We will have the opposite side with length \(x\), and the adjacent side with length \($a\), so the hypotenuse has length \(\sqrt{$a2+x^2}\). With the substitution \[x = {$a}\tan(\theta)\] \[dx = {$a}\sec^2(\theta) \; d\theta\] Therefore: \[\int \frac{dx}{\sqrt{$a2 + x^2}}= \int \frac{{$a}\sec^2\theta d\theta}{\sqrt{$a2 + $a2\tan^2\theta}}\] \[= \int \frac{{$a}\sec^2\theta d\theta}{$a\sec\theta}\] \[= \int \sec\theta d\theta\] \[= \ln\left| \sec\theta+\tan\theta\right|+C\] \[=\ln\left|\frac{\sqrt{$a2+x^2}}{$a}+\frac{x}{$a}\right|+C \]

You take a group of 20 people going to the movies. Kids' tickets cost $DOLLAR 4.- each, and adults tickets $DOLLAR 6.- each. Your total cost is $DOLLAR 96.- .  The number of kids in your group is  \{ ans_rule(6) \}  EOT ANS(num_cmp("12"));  TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  Hint:  Set up and solve a linear system. EOT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD Let \(x\) denote the number of kids and \(y\) the number of adults.   We obtain the linear system \[ \begin{array}{rrcl} x&+y&=&20\\ 4x&+6y&=&96\\ \end{array} \]  Solving it shows that there are \(8\) adults and \(12\) kids in your group.

A ball is shot straight up into the air with initial velocity of  \(!{$initialSpeed}\) ft/sec.  Assuming that the air resistance  can be ignored, how high does it go? $PAR \{ans_rule(30)\} $PAR Hint:  The acceleration due to gravity is 32 ft per second squared. EOT  ANS(num_cmp($height));  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOF')); $SOL  First, recall the relationship between position,  instantaneous velocity, and instantaneous acceleration.  If  \( s(t) \) is the position of the ball at time t (i.e. the height), \( v(t) \)  the velocity, and \( a(t) \) the acceleration, then:  \[   \begin{aligned}     v(t) & = s'(t) \\     a(t) & = v'(t) = s''(t)   \end{aligned} \]  So in our specific problem, we are reminded that the acceleration due to gravity is a constant 32 ft per second squared, in the negative direction. So, we know that \( a(t) = -32 \).  In order to find out how high the ball goes, we will need to first find out what the formula for instantaneous velocity looks like.  Using the relationship above, and the fact that the antiderivative of a constant \( D \) is \( Dx + C \) for another  constant \( C \), we get:  \[   v(t) = -32t + C_1 \]  To find the constant \( C_1 \), notice that we are told that the initial velocity of the ball is \(!{$initialSpeed}\) ft/sec. Therefore, \(v(0) = -32(0) + C_1 = C_1 = $initialSpeed\).  So, the formula for velocity is:  \[   v(t) = -32t + $initialSpeed \]  Now, we need to find the formula for the position of the ball.  This is \( s(t) \), the antiderivative of the velocity formula we just found.  Using the general rules for finding antiderivatives, we see that:  \[   s(t) = -16t^2 + {$initialSpeed}t + C_2 \]  Again, we need to find out what the constant, \( C_2 \) in this case, is equal to.  We can assume that the ball is shot from the ground, which is at height 0.  Therefore, the initial height of the ball, \( s(0) \), is 0 making the constant \( C_2 = 0 \).  Therefore, the final formula for position is:  \[   s(t) = -16t^2+{$initialSpeed}t \]  Finally, to find out how high the ball goes, we need to think about what happens when the ball reaches its maximum height.  At that point, the ball will pause for just an instant before starting to fall back to the ground. It that instant, the velocity of the ball is 0.  So, if we determine the time at which the ball has velocity 0, and then find its height at that time, we will know how high the ball goes. $PAR To find out when the velocity of the ball is 0, we set the velocity formula equal to 0 and compute as follows:  \[   \begin{aligned}     v(t) &= 0 \\     -32t + $initialSpeed &= 0 \\     32t &= $initialSpeed \\     t &= \frac{$initialSpeed}{32} = !{$topTime:%5.4f}   \end{aligned} \]  Therefore, the maximum height of the ball is:  \[   s(!{$topTime:%5.4f}) =   -16(!{$topTime:%5.4f})^2+{$initialSpeed}(!{$topTime:%5.4f}) = !{$height:%5.4f} \]

Consider the function \( f(x) \) whose second derivative is \( f''(x) = $a1 x + $b1 \sin (x) \). If \( f(0) = $n1\) and  \( f'(0) = $m1\), what is  \( f(  $p1 ) \)? \{ans_rule(30) \}  EOT $ans = $a1 * ($p1)**3/6 - $b1 * sin($p1) +($m1+$b1)*$p1 +$n1; ANS(num_cmp($ans));  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOF')); $SOL  This problem has two parts.  The first is finding the function \( f'(x)  \) based on the given function \( f''(x) \) and the information given  about \( f'(0) \).  The second part is using this function and the  information given about \( f(0) \) to find the function \( f(x) \).  We  can then just plug in the point $p1 to find the desired value. $PAR Recall that the derivative of \( \cos(x)\) is \( -\sin(x) \).  Therefore,  the general antiderivative of \($a1 x + $b1 \sin (x) \) is going to be: $PAR \[    f'(x) = \frac{$a1}{2}x^2 - $b1 \cos(x) + C_1 \] Now, since \( f'(0) = $m1 \) we plug 0 in and solve for \( C_1 \) to find the specific antiderivative.  This yeilds: $PAR \[   \begin{aligned}     f'(0) & = $m1 \\     \frac{$a1}{2}(0)^2 - $b1 \cos(0) + C_1 & = $m1 \\     -$b1 + C_1&  = $m1 \\     C_1 & = $m1 + $b1 = \{ $m1+$b1\} \\   \end{aligned} \] $PAR Therefore, the formula \( f'(x) \) is given by \( f'(x) =  \frac{$a1}{2}x^2 - $b1\cos(x) + \{ $m1+$b1 \} \). $PAR Now, on to part two.  We again take the antiderivative of this, this time  recalling that the derivative of \( \sin(x) \) is \( \cos(x) \).   Therefore, the general antiderivative of \( f'(x) \) is given by: $PAR \[   f(x) = \frac{$a1}{2(3)}x^3 - $b1\sin(x) + \{$m1+$b1\}x + C_2 \] $PAR Again, using the information we have about \( f(0) \), we find the specific function \( f(x) \) by solving for \( C_2 \). $PAR \[   \begin{aligned}     f(0) & = $n1 \\     \frac{$a1}{6}(0)^3 - $b1\sin(0) + \{$m1+$b1\}(0) + C_2 & = 0 \\     C_2 & = $n1 \\   \end{aligned} \] $PAR Therefore, the function \(f(x) \) is given by: $PAR \[   f(x) = \frac{$a1}{6}x^3 - $b1\sin(x) + \{$m1+$b1\}x + $n1 \] $PAR We now plug in $p1 to get: $PAR \[   f($p1) = \frac{$a1}{6}($p1)^3 - $b1\sin($p1) + \{$m1+$b1\}($p1) + $n1	          = !{$ans%5.2f} \]

\{htmlLink("http://www.math.utah.edu/online/1010/gravity/", "Recall")\} that the height \(h(t)\) at the time \(t\) of a rock tossed into the air at time \(0\) from a height \(h_0\)  at an initial velocity \(v_0\)  is given by \[h(t) = h_0 + v_0t - 16 t^2.\] Time is measured in seconds, height in feet, and velocity in feet per second.  The positive direction is up, so if the rock is moving down then its velocity is negative. The magic number 16 in this equation is due to the mass and radius of earth and would be different for example on Mars or on the Moon.  The velocity of the rock at time \(t\) is given by \[v(t) = v_0 -32t.\]    Suppose you throw a rock upward from a height of 64 feet with an initial velocity of 48 feet per second.  The rock will hit the ground after \{ ans_rule(10) \} seconds. EOT ANS(num_cmp(4));  TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  Hint: Solve a  \{htmlLink("http://www.math.utah.edu/online/1010/quadeq", "quadratic equation.")\} EOT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD Mathematically the ground corresponds to the height of zero.  We simply set \(h\) to zero in the height formula and obtain: \[0 = h_0 + v_0t - 16 t^2= 64 +48t -16t^2.\] This is a \{htmlLink("http://www.math.utah.edu/online/1010/quadeq", "quadratic equation")\} that has the solutions \(t=-1\) and \(t=4\). The negative solution has no physical significance.  Thus the rock hits the ground after 4 seconds.  (You can get this result also by applying the \{htmlLink("http://www.math.utah.edu/online/1010/formula", "quadratic formula.")\})

Two zeros of the polynomial  \[p(x) = x^4-4x^3-24x^2+20x+7\] are \(1\) and \(7\).  The other two zeros are real, but irrational.    The smaller is \{ ans_rule(20) \}, and the larger is EOT ANS(num_cmp(-2-sqrt(3)));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));   \{ ans_rule(20) \}. EOT ANS(num_cmp(-2+sqrt(3)));   BEGIN_TEXT;  $BBOLD Hint: $EBOLD Divide \(p\) by two linear factors or by one quadratic factor. END_TEXT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));   $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD Since \(1\) and \(7\) are zeros of \(p\) we can divide by \(x-7\) and \(x-1\) using synthetic division.  (We could also divide by \[(x-1)(x-7) = x^2-8x+7,\] using long division.)   We obtain  \[\begin{array}{rrrrrr}     & 1  & -4  & -24  & 20  & 7  \\ 1:  &    & 1   & -3  & -27  & -7  \\     & 1  & -3  & -27 & -7   & 0 \\ 7:  &    & 7   & 28  &  7   &  \\     & 1  & 4   &  1  &  0   &\\ \end{array} \]  Thus  \[p(x) = (x-1)(x-7)(x^2+4x+1).\]  We can find the zeros of the quadratic factor by the quadratic formula or by completing the square.  They are  \[x= -2 \pm \sqrt{3}.\]

Suppose \( y = \ln(\coth x) \).  Find \(D_{x}y\). $PAR Answer: \(D_{x}y = \)\{ans_rule(20)\}.   EOT  $ans = "-sech(x)/sinh(x)";  ANS(fun_cmp($ans));  TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Hint: $EBOLD Recall the derivative of \( \coth(x) \) and don't ever forget the derivative of \( \ln u \) EOT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Solution: $EBOLD  \( D_{x} \ln u = \frac{\hbox{d}u}{u} \). And if  \( u =  \coth x  = \frac{\cosh x}{\sinh x} \) then  \( \hbox{d} u =  - \frac{1}{\sinh^2 x} \).   Cancelation gives \( D_{x}y = \frac{-1}{(\cosh x)(\sinh x)} \)

On the other hand, the image of \(f\) is a subgroup of the cyclic group \( \{ cyclic( $n ) \} \). \{ beginproblem() \} \{ textbook_ref_exact("Rogawski ET 2e", "8.4","14") \} $PAR Calculate the Taylor polynomials \( T_2(x) \) and \( T_3(x) \) centered at \( x = $a \) for \( f(x) = $f \). $PAR  \( T_2(x) = \) \{ans_rule(80)\}  \( T_3(x) = T_2(x) + \) \{ans_rule(60)\} END_TEXT Context()->normalStrings;  ANS($red_a->cmp); #ANS($ans3->cmp); ANS($red_c->cmp);  Context()->texStrings; SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR $SOL Recall the general formula for the Taylor polynomial centered at \(x\) = a: \[ T(x) = f(a) + \frac{f'(a)}{1!} (x-a) + \frac{f''(a)}{2!} (x-a)^2 + ... + \frac{f^n(a)}{n!} (x-a)^n \]  \[ f(x) = $f \] \[ f'(x) = $df \] \[ f''(x) = $df2 \] \[ f'''(x) = $df3 \]  So, in this case, \( f(x) = $f \) and   \( T_2(x) = A + B(x-$a) + C(x-$a)^2\)   where   \(A=f($a)=$bans0=$ans0\)   \(B=f'($a)=$bans1=$ans1\)   \(C=\frac{f''($a)}{2!}=$bans2=$ans2\)   Thus,   \[ T_2(x) = $bans0 + $bans1 (x - $a) + $bans2 (x - $a)^2 \]  or,  \[ T_2(x) = $red_a \]  Similarly,   \( T_3(x) = D + E(x-$a) + F(x-$a)^2 + G(x-$a)^3\)   where   \(D=f($a)=$bans0=$ans0\)   \(E=f'($a)=$bans1=$ans1\)   \(F=\frac{f''($a)}{2!}=$bans2=$ans2\)   \(G=\frac{f'''($a)}{3!}=$bans3=$ans3\)   Thus,   \[ T_3(x) = $bans0 + $bans1 (x - $a) + $bans2 (x - $a)^2 + $bans3  (x - $a)^3\]  or,  \[ T_3(x) = T_2(x) ? {$ans3} (x-$a)^3 \]

Follow the steps below to answer the following question: $PAR For what values \( a \) and \( b \) is the line \( $c x + y = b \) tangent to the curve \( y = a x^{$n} \) at the point with \( x = $d \)? $PAR (A) Use the limit process, as we did in class, to find the slope of the tangent line to \( y = a x^{$n} \) when \( x = $d \). (Your answer will contain an \(a\).) $PAR The slope of the tangent line to \( y = a x^{$n} \) when \( x = $d \) is \{ ans_rule(20) \}. $PAR (B) What is the slope of the line \( $c x + y = b \)? $PAR The slope of this line is \{ ans_rule(20) \}. $PAR (C) In order for the line \( $c x + y = b \) to be tangent to the curve \( y = a x^{$n} \) at \( x = $d \), we need for the slope of the tangent line to \( y = a x^{$n} \) at \( x = $d \) to be the same as the slope of the line \( $c x + y = b \). $PAR Thus in comparing (A) and (B), we find that \( a =\) \{ ans_rule(20) \} $PAR (D) Lastly, in order for the line \( $c x + y = b \) to be tangent to the curve \( y = a x^{$n} \) at \( x = $d \), the graphs of \( $c x + y = b \) and \( y = a x^{$n} \) must have the same \(y\)-coordinate at \(x = $d\). $PAR Comparing the \(y\)-coordinates of the two graphs tells us that \( b =\) \{ ans_rule(20) \}

The dihedral group   \(\{dihedral( $m )\}\)  of order \($mtwo\) is  generated by two elements \(a, b\) satisfying the relations \(   a^{$m} = b^2 = 1,  ba = a^{-1}b. \). For each of the following subgroups \(H\) of \(\{dihedral( $m )\}\), determine if each of the following pairs of elements represent the same  left \(H\)-coset:    \{ begintable(5) \}  \{   row( "\(H\)",         "Element \(\#1\)",         "Element \(\#2\)" ,         "Answer (Y/N)") \} \{   row( "\(\langle a^{$i} \rangle\)",         "\(a^{$u} \)",         "\(a^{$g} \)",         ans_rule(10) ) \} \{   row( "\(\langle a^{$i} \rangle\)",        "\(a^{$u} b\)",         "\(a^{$g} b\)",         ans_rule(10) ) \} \{   row( "\(\langle a^{$i} b\rangle\)",        "\(a^{$u} \)",         "\(a^{$g} \)",         ans_rule(10) ) \} \{   row( "\(\langle a^{$i} b\rangle\)",        "\(a^{$u} b\)",         "\(a^{$g} b\)",         ans_rule(10) ) \}  \{ endtable() \}     END_TEXT  # BEGIN_HINT # END_HINT   ANS(str_cmp($ans1) ); ANS(str_cmp($ans1) ); ANS(str_cmp($ans3) ); ANS(str_cmp($ans3) );   SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR SOLUTION $PAR   Let \(G\) be a group.  For any subgroup \(K\) of \(G\) and any elements \( x, y\in G\),    (*) \( \) \( \) \( \) \( xH = yH \) if and only if  \( y^{-1}x\in H \).    Let us apply this to the case where \(G\) is the dihedral group of order \( 2m\). Apply (*) to \(   H = \langle a^{$i} \rangle \) and it follows that \(   a^{u}H = a^{g}H \) if and only if \(   a^{u - g}\in \langle a^{i} \rangle, \) which happens if and only if \(   u - g \equiv 0 \pmod{ gcd(m, i) }. \) Similarly, \(   a^{u} bH = a^{g} bH \) if and only if \(  \langle a^{i} \rangle \) contains \(   (a^{g} b)^{-1}(a^{u}b) = b a^{u-g} b = a^{g-u}, \) so once again we arrive at the same condition, that \(   u - g \equiv 0 \pmod{ gcd(m, i) }. \)

If a 1000-pound capsule weighs only 165 pounds on the moon, how much work is done in propelling this capsule out of the moon's gravitational field?  (Note: The radius of the moon is roughly 1080 miles) $PAR The amount of work is  \{ans_rule(30)\} mile-pounds. EOT $ans = "1.782*10**5"; ANS(num_cmp($ans, relTol=>4));  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $PAR $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD At \( x = 1080 \) mi, \( F = 165 \), so \( k = 165(1080)^2 \approx 1.925 \times 10^8\).  So the work done in mi-lb is   \[ 1.925 \times 10^8  $ds\int_{1080}^{\infty}\frac{1}{x^2} \hbox{d}x = 1.925 \times 10^8 \]  \[=  $ds\int_{1}^{\infty}\left(\frac{1}{x} - \frac{1}{x+1}\right) \hbox{d}x  \left[ -x^{-1} \right]_{1080}^{\infty} = \frac{1.925 \times 10^8}{1080} \]  \( \approx 1.782 \times 10^5 \)  mi-lb.

question_text:
\{ textbook_ref_exact("Rogawski ET 2e", "14.8","34") \} $PAR A plane with equation \( rac{x}{a}+  rac{y}{b}+  rac{z}{c}=1\) \((a, b, c >0)\)  together with the positive coordinate planes forms a tetrahedron of volume \(V= rac16 abc\) (as shown in the Figure below) $PAR Find the plane that minimizes \(V\) if the plane is constrained to pass through a point \(P = ($alpha,$beta,$gamma)\) . $PAR \{image("image_14_8_31.png", width=>275, height=>228)\} $PAR The plane \{ans_rule()\} \(=1\) $PAR  END_TEXT  Context()->normalStrings; ANS($answer->cmp);  Context()->texStrings; SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR $SOL The plane \( rac{x}{a}+ rac{y}{b}+ rac{z}{c}=1\) must pass through the point \(P( $alpha ,$beta ,$gamma )\), hence \[  rac{$alpha }{a}+ rac{$beta }{b}+ rac{$gamma }{c}=1 \] We thus must minimize the function \(V( a,b,c )= rac{1}{6}abc\) subject to the constraint \(g( a,b,c )= rac{$alpha }{a}+ rac{$beta }{b}+ rac{$gamma }{c}=1\), \(a>0\), \(b>0\), \(c>0\). $PAR $BBOLD [Step 1.] $EBOLD Write out the Lagrange Equations. $PAR We have \(
abla V= \left<  rac{1}{6}bc, rac{1}{6}ac, rac{1}{6}ab ight>\) and \(
abla g= \left< - rac{$alpha }{{a}^2},- rac{$beta }{{b}^2},- rac{$gamma }{{c}^2} ight>\), hence the Lagrange Condition \(
abla V=\lambda 
abla g\) yields the following equations: \[  egin{array}{rcl}  rac{1}{6}bc&{}={}&- rac{$alpha }{{a}^2}\lambda \ 
oalign{\medskip}  rac{1}{6}ac&=&- rac{$beta }{{b}^2}\lambda \ 
oalign{\medskip}  rac{1}{6}ab&=&- rac{$gamma }{{c}^2}\lambda \end{array} \quad\Rightarrow\quad  egin{array}{rcl} \lambda &{}={}&- rac{{a}^2bc}{6\cdot $alpha}\ 
oalign{\medskip} \lambda &=&- rac{{b}^2{ac}}{6\cdot$beta}\ 
oalign{\medskip} \lambda &=&- rac{{c}^2ab}{6\cdot $gamma} \end{array} \] $BBOLD [Step 2.] $EBOLD Solve for \(a\), \(b\), \(c\) using the constraint. $PAR The Lagrange equations imply the following equations: \[ rac{{a}^2bc}{$alpha }= rac{{c}^2ab}{$gamma }\] \[ rac{{b}^2{ac}}{$beta }= rac{{c}^2ab}{$gamma }\] We simplify the two equations to obtain \[abc( $gamma a-$alpha c )=0\] \[abc( $gamma b-$beta c )=0\] Since \(abc
e 0\), these equations imply that \[  egin{array}{rclcrcl} $gamma a-$alpha c&{}={}&0&\Rightarrow& a&{}={}& rac{$alpha }{$gamma }c\ 
oalign{\medskip} $gamma b-$beta c&=&0&\Rightarrow& b&=& rac{$beta }{$gamma }c \qquad \mathbf{(1)}\end{array} \] We now substitute in the constraint \( rac{$alpha }{a}+ rac{$beta }{b}+ rac{$gamma }{c}=1\) and solve for \(c\). This gives \[ rac{$alpha }{ rac{$alpha }{$gamma }c}+ rac{$beta }{ rac{$beta }{$gamma }c}+ rac{$gamma }{c}=1\] \[ rac{$gamma }{c}+ rac{$gamma }{c}+ rac{$gamma }{c}=1\] \[ rac{\{3*$gamma\}}{c}=1\quad\Rightarrow\quad c=\{3*$gamma\}\] We find \(a\) and \(b\) using \(\mathbf{(1)}\): \[ a= rac{$alpha }{$gamma }\cdot \{3*$gamma\} =\{3*$alpha\} ,\quad  b= rac{$beta }{$gamma }\cdot \{3*$gamma\} =\{3*$beta\}\] We obtain the solution \[P=( \{3*$alpha\} ,\{3*$beta\} ,\{3*$gamma\} )\]  $BBOLD [Step 3.] $EBOLD Conclusions.

Directions (or $BITALIC bearings$EITALIC) on Earth are measured in degrees, running from zero to \(360^\circ\), clockwise, starting with \(0^\circ\) being due North.  So due East for example, is \(90^\circ\), due South \(180^\circ\), and Northwest is \(315^\circ\).    You are swinging a rock clockwise (looking from above) around your head and you are trying to hit a broom stick \( $a \) feet due east of you. The rock moves in a circle of a radius of \( $b \) feet around your head. Consider again the formula for the solution of a quadratic equation:  \[x= \frac{-b+\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\]  For each of the WeBWorK phrases below enter a T (true) if the phrase describes \(x\), correctly, and a F (false) otherwise.    You need to get all answers correct before obtaining credit.	      \{ ans_rule(4) \}   -b+sqrt(b**2-4*a*c)/2a    EOT  ANS(str_cmp("F"));   TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));     \{ ans_rule(4) \}  (-b+sqrt(b**2-4*a*c))/2a   EOT ANS(str_cmp("F"));   TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));     \{ ans_rule(4) \}   (-b+sqrt(b**2-4*a*c))/(2a)   EOT ANS(str_cmp("T"));   SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD     -b+sqrt(b**2-4*a*c)/2a  means \[-b +\frac{\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2} \times a\] which is quite different.  The reason for the confusion is that division and multiplication have the same precedence and proceed from left to right unless otherwise indicated with parentheses.  Thus we divide by 2, and then multiply the result with a.  Also the scope of the division is only the square root since division comes before the addition to \(b\).   (-b+sqrt(b**2-4*a*c))/2a is a little better in that \(-b\) is included in the numerator, but the final \(a\) is still in the numerator rather than the denominator.  The expression means: \[\frac{-b +\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2} \times a\].   The last expression,  (-b+sqrt(b**2-4*a*c))/(2a) is the correct answer for Problem 23.

You build a box that is $a feet long, $b feet wide, and $c feet high. The distance from the top left front corner to the top right back corner is   \{ ans_rule(15) \} feet. EOT ANS(num_cmp(sqrt($a*$a+$b*$b)));     TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  The distance from the bottom left front corner to the top right back corner is   \{ ans_rule(15) \} feet. EOT ANS(num_cmp(sqrt($a*$a+$b*$b+$c*$c)));    TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  Hint: Draw a picture and apply the Pythagorean Theorem. EOT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD For this problem it is best to draw a picture of the box and the distances involved.  The first question can be answered by drawing the top face of the box and noticing that the distance is the length of the diagonal which can be computed by the Pythagorean theorem as \(\sqrt{4^2+5^2} = \sqrt{41}\). To obtain the answer to the second question draw another right triangle, one side of which is the diagonal whose length you just computed, and the other side of which is the height of the box. Applying the Pythagorean Theorem again we obtain \(\sqrt{\sqrt{41}^2+8^2}= \sqrt{41+64}= \sqrt{105}.\) Note that this length equals \(\sqrt{4^2+5^2+8^2}\).  In general, the length \(d\) of the space diagonal of a box with the dimensions \(a\), \(b\), and \(c\) is \[d = \sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}.\]

${BTITLE}Using Contexts in MathObjects${ETITLE} $PAR  A MathObjects context controls the names and values of variables and constants, the functions that are available, the mathematical operations that are available, the way parentheses and angle brackets are interpreted, the strings that are allowed, and various other settings involving tolerances and display formats.  We list some of the more commonly used features of contexts below.  \{ BeginList("OL") \}  $ITEM Specifying which variables are defined in the context.  By default, the variable x is in the Numeric context.  In the first example, we add the variable y to the context, while the second example sets t as the only variable allowed (if a student enters a function of x, they will get an error message).  Whenever ${BCODE}Context()${ECODE} is typed, it refers to the current context. ${BPRE} Context("Numeric"); Context()->variables->add(y=>"Real");  Context()->variables->are(t=>"Real"); ${EPRE}   $ITEMSEP $ITEM Adding strings (words) to the context.  By default, the Numeric context already has the case-insensitive strings "NONE", "DNE", "INF", "INFINITY", and perhaps some others.  We give an example of adding the case-insensitive strings "True" and "T" to the context, and letting "T" be an alias for "True".  If you have a lot of strings to add to the context, use the \{ htmlLink('http://webwork.maa.org/pod/pg_TRUNK/macros/parserAutoStrings.pl.html','auto strings parser',"TARGET=~~"_new~~"") \}   ${BPRE} Context("Numeric"); Context()->strings->add(   True => {},   T => {alias=>"True"} ); ${EPRE}   $ITEMSEP  $ITEM Disabling operations and functions.  You can require students to enter their answers in a particular form by disabling functions and operations.  We give an example where we do not allow exponentiation, the natural exponential and logarithm, and aany trigonometric functions.  For more details, see \{ htmlLink('http://webwork.maa.org/wiki/DisableFunctions','disabling functions and operations',"TARGET=~~"_new~~"") \} ${BPRE} Context("Numeric"); Context()->operators->undefine("^","**"); Context()->functions->disable("exp","log"); Context()->functions->disable("Trig"); ${EPRE}     $ITEMSEP $ITEM Adding named functions to the context.  Suppose we want to add a base two logarithm to the context, so that students could enter ${BCODE}log2( )${ECODE}.  For more details, see \{ htmlLink('http://webwork.maa.org/wiki/AddingFunctions','adding functions to the context',"TARGET=~~"_new~~"") \} ${BPRE} loadMacros( "PGstandard.pl", "MathObjects.pl", "parserFunction.pl", );  Context("Numeric"); parserFunction("log2(x)"=>"log(x)/log(2)"); ${EPRE}   $ITEMSEP $ITEM Specifying the values the variables may take (i.e., domain of function evaluation).  For formulas, WebWork checks student answers against the correct answer by pointwise comparison at many points.  The default is that each variable is evaluated on the interval [-1,1].  This default should be changed if the formula is not defined on the part of the interval [-1,1] or if the function values are not between \( 10^{-4} \) and \( 10^{6} \), e.g., if there is a vertical asymptote or the formula is close to being identically zero.  It is also possible to specify the domain for each individual function being compared to the student's answers, as we shall see later. ${BPRE} Context("Numeric"); Context()->variables->set(x=>{limits=>[2,5]}); ${EPRE}    $ITEMSEP $ITEM Specifying the numerical tolerances for answers being accepted as correct.  The student's answer may differ slightly from the correct answer and still be marked correct.  The default tolerance is a relative tolerance of 0.1 percent of the correct answer, which may allow many incorrect answers to be marked correct when the correct answer is very large.  It is also possible to specify an absolute tolerance, in which case the student's answer must be correct to however many decimal places you specify.  The numerical tolerance may also be specified at the time of answer evaluation. ${BPRE} Context("Numeric"); Context()->flags->set(   tolerance=>0.0001,   tolType=>relative );  Context()->flags->set(   tolerance=>0.0000001,   tolType=>absolute ); ${EPRE}   \{ EndList("OL") \}      $PAR ${BTITLE}Online References${ETITLE} \{ BeginList('UL') \}  $ITEM \{ htmlLink('http://webwork.maa.org/wiki/VariablesOtherThanX','Variables in the context',"TARGET=~~"_new~~"") \}  $ITEM \{ htmlLink('http://webwork.maa.org/wiki/StringsInContext','Adding strings to the context',"TARGET=~~"_new~~"") \}  $ITEM \{ htmlLink('http://webwork.maa.org/pod/pg_TRUNK/macros/parserAutoStrings.pl.html','Parser Auto Strings',"TARGET=~~"_new~~"") \}  $ITEM \{ htmlLink('http://webwork.maa.org/wiki/DisableFunctions','Disabling functions and operators',"TARGET=~~"_new~~"") \}  $ITEM \{ htmlLink('http://webwork.maa.org/wiki/AddingFunctions','Adding functions to the context',"TARGET=~~"_new~~"") \}  $ITEM \{ htmlLink('http://webwork.maa.org/wiki/FormulaTestPoints','Formula test points',"TARGET=~~"_new~~"") \}  $ITEM \{ htmlLink('http://webwork.maa.org/wiki/NumericalTolerance','Numerical tolerance',"TARGET=~~"_new~~"") \}  $ITEM \{ htmlLink('http://webwork.maa.org/wiki/Context_flags','Context flags',"TARGET=~~"_new~~"") \}    \{ EndList('UL') \}

\{ textbook_ref_exact("Rogawski ET 2e", "6.4","27") \} $PAR Use both the Shell and Disk Methods to calculate the volume of the solid obtained by rotating the region under the graph of \(f (x) = $n - x^3\) for \(0 \le x \le {$n}^{\frac{1}{3}}\)  about the \(x\)-axis and the \(y\)-axis. $PAR  Using the disk method, the volume \(D_x\) of the solid obtained by rotating the region about the \(x\)-axis is \(\int_0^a g(x)dx\)  (this is the initial integral when you setup the problem), where  a =\{ans_rule()\}  g(x)=\{ans_rule(80)\}  \(D_x\)=\{ans_rule()\} $PAR Using the shell method, the volume \(S_x\) of the solid obtained by rotating the region about the \(x\)-axis is \(\int_0^b h(y)dy\) (this is the initial integral when you setup the problem), where  b= \{ans_rule()\}  h(y)=\{ans_rule(80)\}  \(S_x\)=\{ans_rule()\} $PAR Using the disk method, the volume \(D_y\) of the solid obtained by rotating the region about the \(y\)-axis is \(\int_0^A G(y)dy\) (this is the initial integral when you setup the problem), where  A =\{ans_rule()\}  G(y)=\{ans_rule(80)\}  \(D_y\)=\{ans_rule()\} $PAR Using the shell method, the volume \(S_y\) of the solid obtained by rotating the region about the \(y\)-axis is \(\int_0^B H(x)dx\) (this is the initial integral when you setup the problem), where  B= \{ans_rule()\}  H(x)=\{ans_rule(80)\}  \(S_y\)=\{ans_rule()\}    END_TEXT  ANS(std_num_cmp($n**(1/3))); ANS(function_cmp("pi*(($n-x**3)**2)","x", 1, 2)); $v1=Real(pi*9*$n**(7/3)/14); ANS($v1->cmp);  ANS(std_num_cmp($n)); ANS(function_cmp("2*pi*y*(($n-y)**(1/3))","y", 1, 2)); ANS($v1->cmp);    ANS(std_num_cmp($n)); ANS(function_cmp("pi*(($n-y)**(2/3))","y", 1, 2)); $v2=Real(pi*3*$n**(5/3)/5); ANS($v2->cmp);  ANS(std_num_cmp($n**(1/3))); ANS(function_cmp("2*pi*x*($n-x**3)","x", 1, 2));  ANS($v2->cmp);  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR $SOL  (a) Rotating the region about \(x\)-axis:  Using the disk method, the cross sections are disks with radius \(R = $n - x^3\); hence the volume of the solid, \(D_x\), is \[ \begin{array}{ll} D_x&=\pi\int_0^{$n^{\frac{1}{3}}}($n-x^3)^2dx\cr &=\pi\left.\left($n6 x-$n5 x^4+\frac17x^7\right)\right|_0^{$n^{\frac{1}{3}}}\cr &=\frac{9\pi}{14}$n^{\frac{7}{3}} =$v1 \end{array} \] With the shell method, each shell has radius \(y\) and height \(($n - y)^{\frac13}\). The volume of the solid, \(S_x\), is \[ \begin{array}{ll} S_x&=2\pi\int_0^{$n}y($n-y)^{\frac{1}{3}}dy \end{array} \] Let \(u=$n-y \). Then \(dy=-du,y=$n-u\) and \[ \begin{array}{ll} S_x&=2\pi\int_{0}^{$n}y($n-y)^{\frac{1}{3}}dy\cr &=-2\pi\int_{$n}^0 ($n-u) u^{\frac{1}{3}}du\cr &=2\pi\int_0^{$n} ($n u^{\frac{1}{3}}-u^{\frac{4}{3}})du\cr &=2\pi ($n \frac{3}{4} u^{\frac{4}{3}}-\frac{3}{7}u^{\frac{7}{3}}) |_0^{$n}\cr &=\frac{9\pi}{14}$n^{\frac{7}{3}}\cr &=$v1 \end{array} \] $br (b) Rotating the region about \(y\)-axis:  Using the disk method, the cross sections are disks with radius \(R = ($n - y)^{\frac{1}{3}}\). The volume, \(D_y\), is then given by \[ \begin{array}{ll} D_y& =\pi\int_{0}^{$n}($n-y)^{\frac{2}{3}}dy=\cr &=\frac{-\pi 3}{5}($n-y)^{5/3}|_{0}^{$n}\cr &=\frac{6\pi}{5} $n^{\frac{5}{3}}\cr &= $v2 \end{array} \]  With the shell method, each shell has radius x and height \($n-x^3\).The volume of the solid, \(S_y\) is  \[ \begin{array}{ll} S_y&= 2\pi\int_{0}^{$n^{\frac{1}{3}}}x($n-x^3)dx\cr &=2\pi(\frac{$n}{2} x^2-\frac{1}{5} x^5)|_{0}^{$n^{\frac{1}{3}}}\cr &=\frac{6\pi}{5} $n^{\frac{5}{3}}\cr &= $v2 \end{array}

Assume a rock is dropped down a well, but you are on a planet with a gravity constant \(g\) (instead of 32 feet per second squared) and a speed of sound \(c\) (instead of 1100 feet per second), and that you hear the impact of the rock after \(t\) seconds.  Then the depth of the well is  \{ ans_rule(30) \}  feet, where your answer depends on \(c\), \(g\), and \(t\).  $BBOLD Note:$EBOLD Thus you will have a formula that you can use to determine the depth of a well on any planet and in any atmosphere.  EOT  ANS(fun_cmp("( -  c /  sqrt(2g) + sqrt(c^2 /( 2 g)  + ct))^2", limits=>[[100,200],[20,4],[1.3]], vars=>["c","g","t"]));    SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD Clearly, \[t = t_d+t_s \] where \(t_d\) is the time that the rock takes to reach the bottom, and \(t_s\) is the time the sound of the impact takes to travel back to your ear.  The latter is easy to determine,: \[t_s = \frac{d}{c}.\] The  equation governing the flight of the rock is \[h(t)  =-\frac{g}{2}t^2  + v_0 t + h_0.\]  In our case the original height and velocity are zero, and instead of height we are interested in depth, which is the negative of height. Hence,  when the rock reaches the bottom of the well we have that  \[h(t) = -\frac{g}{2}t_d^2 = -d.\] Thus \[t_d=\sqrt{\frac{2d}{g}}.\] We have to solve the equation \[t_s+t_d = \sqrt{\frac{2d}{g}} + \frac{d}{c} = t\] for \(d\). The key step is to recognize that  this is a  quadratic equation, not in \(d\) but in  the square root of \(d\).  Let's call it \(u\): \[u = \sqrt{d}\]  Then the equation turns into: \[t-\sqrt{\frac{2}{ g}} u - \frac{u^2}{ c} = 0.\] We can solve this equation using the quadratic formula. You may be comfortable doing that, and while I think that you are wasting your energy burdening your mind with arcane information like the quadratic formula, for the purposes of this assignment that's just fine. As for myself, I can never remember that formula, and memorizing formulas is error prone anyway. What if I misremember or misapply a formula? So in this discussion, we complete the square.  We obtain after multiplying with \(-c\) and rearranging:  \[\begin{array}{rcl} u^2 + \sqrt{\frac{2 }{  g} } cu - ct &=& 0 \\ u^2 + \sqrt{\frac{2 }{ g} }cu +  \frac{c^2}{ 2g} &=&  \frac{c^2}{ 2g}  + ct  \\ \left(u + \frac{1 }{  \sqrt{2g}}c \right)^2 &=&  ct + \frac{c^2 }{ 2g} \end{array} \] and therefore: \[u = - \frac{1  }{  \sqrt{2g}}c \pm \sqrt{   ct + \frac{c^2}{ 2g}}.\] We know that if \(t\) is 0 then \(d\), and therefore \(u\), must be 0 also. To get \(u=0\) we must choose the positive sign.  The solution with the negative sign is an artifact of solving a quadratic equation.  We also need to square on both sides of this equation to get \(d\).  After a slight rearrangement we obtain:  \[d = u^2 = \left( - \frac{ c }{  \sqrt{2g}} + \sqrt{\frac{c^2 }{ 2 g}  + ct} \right)^2.\]   This is the desired formula.

\{ beginproblem() \} \{ textbook_ref_exact("Rogawski ET 2e", "13.3","23") \} $PAR Find a path that traces the circle in the plane \(y=$y0\) with radius \(r=$r\) and center \(($x0,$y0,$z0)\) with constant speed $speed. $PAR \(\bf r\it_1(s)=\left< \right.\) \{ans_rule()\},\{ans_rule()\},\{ans_rule()\} \(\left. \right>\)   END_TEXT  Context()->normalStrings; ANS($ansx->cmp); ANS($ansy->cmp); ANS($ansz->cmp); Context()->texStrings;  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR $SOL  We start with the following parametrization of the circle:  \(\bf r\it(t)=\left<$x0,$y0,$z0\right>+$r\left<\cos t,0,\sin t\right>=\left<$x0+$r\cos t, $y0, $z0+$r\sin t\right>\)  We need to reparametrize the curve by making a substitution on \(t=\phi(s)\), so that the new parametrization \(\bf r\it_1(s)=\bf r\it(\phi(s))\) satisfies \(||\bf r\it_1'(s)||=$speed\) for all \(s\). We find \(\bf r\it_1'\) using the Chain Rule:  \(\bf r\it_1'(s)=\frac{d}{ds}\bf r\it(\phi(s))=\phi'(s)\bf r\it'(\phi(s))\)  Next, we differentiate \(\bf r\it(t)\) and then replace \(t\) by \(\phi(s)\):  \(\bf r\it'(t)=\left<-$r\sin t, 0, $r\cos t\right> \)  \(\bf r\it'(\phi(s))=\left<-$r\sin(\phi(s)), 0, $r\cos(\phi(s))\right> \)  Now, we get: \(\bf r\it_1'(s)=\phi'(s)\left<-$r\sin(\phi(s)), 0, $r\cos(\phi(s))\right>=$r\phi'(s)\left<-\sin(\phi(s)), 0,\cos(\phi(s))\right>\)  Hence,  \( ||\bf r\it_1'(s)||=$r|\phi'(s)|\sqrt{(-\sin(s))^2+(\cos(s))^2}=$r|\phi'(s)|\)  To satisfy \(||\bf r\it_1'(s)||=$speed\) for all \(s\), we choose \(\phi'(s)=$phi\).  We may take the antiderivative of \(\phi(s)=$phi s\) and obtain the following parametrization:  \(\bf r\it_1(s)=\bf r\it(\phi(s))=r($phi s)=\left<$x0+$r\cos ($phi s), $y0, $z0+$r\sin ($phi s)\right>\)

The percentage, \(P\), of words recognized was recorded as a function of \(t\), the time elapsed in minutes.  The table below shows the averages for 5 different subjects.  This is modeled by \( P=a\ln t +b \).  $PAR $BCENTER \{ begintable(7) \} \{ row( "\(t\), min", @x_top ) \} \{ row( "\(P\)${PERCENT}", @y_top ) \} \{ endtable() \}  \{ begintable(7) \} \{ row( "\(t\), min", @x_bot ) \} \{ row( "\(P\)${PERCENT}", @y_bot ) \} \{ endtable() \} $ECENTER  $PAR (a) Find \( \ln{t} \) for each value of \( t \) in the table above, and then use linear regression on a calculator to estimate \( a \) and \( b \) in the linear fit \( P= a \ln{t} +b \).  In the blanks below, enter the corresponding values for \( a \) and \( b \):  \( a = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}  \( b = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}  ${BITALIC}(round values to 4 decimal places)$EITALIC  $PAR (b) When does this model (in part a) predict that the subjects will recognize no words?  In \{ ans_rule(20) \} DAYS (1440 minutes = 1 day)  $PAR (c) When does this model (in part a) predict that the subjects will recognize all words?  In \{ ans_rule(20) \} SECONDS.

$BBOLD The Columbia Accident.$EBOLD On January 16, 2003, 81.7 seconds into the ascent, a piece of foam, weighing about 1.7 pounds, and being roughly the size, shape and weight of a large loaf of bread, separated from the bipod ramp of the space shuttle Columbia's external fuel tank and impacted the leading edge of the shuttle's left wing.  At that time the shuttle was traveling at approximately 1,568 mph (Mach 2.46) and was at an altitude of 66,000 feet. Based on film evidence, the foam traveled the 58-foot distance from the ramp to the wing in 0.16 seconds. Assuming a constant acceleration relative to the body of  the space shuttle of \{ans_rule(20)\} feet per second  EOT ANS(num_cmp( $a));   TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); squared, the foam hit the wing at a speed of \{ans_rule(20)\} feet per second,  EOT ANS(num_cmp( $v));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); or \{ans_rule(20)\} miles per hour. Unbeknownst to the astronauts and observers on earth, it struck the wing hard enough to cause the destruction of the Columbia two weeks later during re-entry on February 1, 2003. EOT  ANS(num_cmp( $V));    TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); $PAR Note: A much more involved calculation estimated the speed of the impact to be about 530 mph.  $PAR Remember that ww expects your answer to be within one tenth of one percent of what it considers the true answer.  Calculate your answers based on the given data and assumptions to at least four digits. EOT  TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));   $BBOLD Hint:$EBOLD Figure everything relative to the moving space shuttle, i.e., the origin is traveling with the shuttle.  Acceleration is the derivative of velocity, and velocity is the derivative of displacement.  In this case, the acceleration is constant (by assumption), and the initial velocity and displacement are 0.  After 0.16 seconds the displacement is 58 feet.  There are 3,600 seconds in an hour, and 5280 feet in a mile.  As in many real problems, the problem statement contains extraneous information.  You have to decide what parts of the information are pertinent. EOT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));   $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD Velocity \(v\) is the derivative of displacement \(d\), and acceleration \(a\) is the derivative of velocity.  If the acceleration is constant (and the initial velocity and displacement are 0), then \[v=at\] and \[s=\frac{1}{2} a t^2.\] Substituting \(s=58\) and \(t=1.6\) in the last equation allows us to solve for \[a = \frac{2s}{t} = \frac{2\times 58 }{0.16^2}\approx 4531\hbox{ft/sec}^2.\] (This is more than 140 times the acceleration caused by gravity.  The space shuttle itself was accelerating at only about 40 feet per second squared.  The large acceleration of that bulky and light weight foam was caused by the slip stream, despite the thin air at 66,000 feet.)  Multiplying that acceleration with the time of \(t=0.16\) seconds gives an impact velocity of 725 feet per second. Dividing by 5280 (feet per mile) and multiplying by 3,600 (seconds per hour) gives a speed of 494.3 miles per hour.  That's remarkably close to the "official" estimate of 530 mph.  Calculus is amazing!    $BBOLD Note:$EBOLD The solution of this exercise is referred to as  $BITALIC  a simple calculation $EITALIC in \{htmlLink("http://www.swri.edu/3pubs/ttoday/fall03/LeadingEdge.htm", "this article")\}.

Suppose you take out a ${n}-year loan from C'ville Bank  for $a dollars at an interest rate of $ip percent effective.  To repay the loan, you agree to   make equal annual payments, the first coming in one year.  After  making the 10th payment, you decide to refinance your loan.  In particular, you want to reduce your annual payment  to 1500 dollars for each of the remaining $m payments,  and then make a large final payment at the end of the  original ${n}-year period to pay off the loan. (This  payment will come immediately after the final 1500 dollar loan payment.)  To save money for this large final payment,  you plan to make equal annual deposits into an  account at Richmond Bank earning $iep percent effective. These deposits will occur at the same time as the 1500 dollar  loan payments, i.e.  the first deposit will be one year after you refinance the loan, and  the last will be at the time of your final loan payment.   C'ville Bank will agree to your plan, provided that  their yield rate for the ENTIRE loan is $yp percent effective. What will be the amount of each of the annual deposits to your  account at Richmond Bank?    $PAR Answer =  \{ans_rule(25) \} dollars.

question_text: Let the polynomial \(p\) be defined by \[p(x) = (x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)\] The degree of \(p\) is  \{ ans_rule(4) \}, EOT ANS(num_cmp(4)); TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  its leading coefficient is  \{ ans_rule(4) \}, EOT ANS(num_cmp(1)); TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  and its constant term is  \{ ans_rule(4) \}, EOT ANS(num_cmp(24));  TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  Hint:  You can answer these questions without converting the polynomial to standard form. EOT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD  There are four linear factors.  The highest power of \(x\) can be obtained by picking the factor \(x\) from each of the individual factors, which gives a degree of \(4\).  All those terms \(x\) have the factor \(1\), and so the leading coefficient is \(1^4=1\).  The constant term is the product of the constant terms of the individual factors, i.e., it is 24.  However, if this argument mystifies you you can obtain the same result by converting the polynomial to standard form.  We obtain \[\begin{array}{rcl} p(x) &=& (x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4) \\ &=& \left(x^2-3x+2\right)\left(x^2-7x+12\right) \\ &=& x^4 -3x^3 +2x^2 \\ &&\phantom{x^4} -7x^3+21x^2 -14x \\ &&\phantom{x^4-7x^3}+12x^2 -36x+24 \\ &=& x^4-10x^3+35x^2-50x+24. \end{array} \]  It is often the case in mathematics (and elsewhere) that  brute force works and gives the desired results, but  a lot of work can be saved by applying insight instead.

The height of a triangle is 8 inches less than its base.  The area of the triangle is 192 square inches.  The height of the triangle is \{ ans_rule(10) \} inches EOT ANS(num_cmp(16)); TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); and the base of the triangle is  \{ ans_rule(10) \} inches. EOT ANS(num_cmp(24));  TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  Hint: The area of a triangle equals one half of base times height.  EOT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD The area of a triangle equals one half times base times height. Let's call the base of this particular triangle \(b\).  Then its height equals \(b-8\).  Thus we have to solve the equation \[\frac{b(b-8)}{2} = 192.\] This is an ordinary quadratic equation that we can solve by completing the square: \[ \begin{array}{rcl} b^2-8b &=& 384\\ b^2-8b &=& 384\\ b^2 - 8b + 4^2 &=& 384 + 4^2 \\ \left(b-4\right)^2 &=& 400 \\ b-4 &=& \pm 20 \\ b &=& 4 \pm 20 \\ \end{array} \]  Thus \(b=24\) or \(b=-16\).  The negative value does not make sense here.  The base is 24 inches, and the height 8 inches less, i.e, 16 inches.

Determine the number of possible ring homomorphisms for each pair of rings:    (a) \( \{ cyclic( $a ) \} \rightarrow \{ cyclic( $a ) \} \): \{ ans_rule( 10 ) \}    (b) \( \{ cyclic( $m1 ) \} \rightarrow \{ cyclic( $n1 ) \} \): \{ ans_rule( 10 ) \}    (c) \( \{ cyclic( $m2 ) \} \rightarrow \{ cyclic( $n2 ) \} \): \{ ans_rule( 10 ) \}    Note:  For this problem we do NOT require ring homomorphisms to take the multiplicative identity to the multiplicative identity.   EOT  ANS( $ans[ 0 ]->cmp ); ANS( $ans[ 1 ]->cmp ); ANS( $ans[ 2 ]->cmp );   SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $SOLUTION  If \(f: \{ cyclic( 'm' ) \} \rightarrow  \{ cyclic( 'n' ) \}  \)  is a ring homomorphism then    \[ \begin{aligned} (**) \; f( a 1_{\{ cyclic( 'm' ) \}} ) &= a f( 1_{\{ cyclic( 'm' ) \}} ) \\ &=  a 1_{ \{ cyclic( 'n' ) \} } \end{aligned} \]  Since every element of \( \{ cyclic( 'm' ) \} \) is of the form \( a 1_{\{ cyclic( 'm' ) \}} \) for some integer \( a \), it follows that \( f \) is completely determined by a single value \( F:= f( 1_{\{ cyclic( 'm' ) \}} ) \). $PAR  But not every element of \(  \{ cyclic( 'n' ) \}  \) can be a choice for \( F \): From properties of ring homomorphisms we get  \[ \begin{aligned} 	0_{ \{ cyclic( 'n' ) \} } &= f( 0_{ \{ cyclic( 'm' ) \} } ) \\ 	&= f( m 1_{ \{ cyclic( 'm' ) \} } ) \\ 	&= m f( 1_{ \{ cyclic( 'm' ) \} } ) \\ 	&= mF. \end{aligned} \]    So in order for \( F \in  \{ cyclic( 'n' ) \}  \) to be a valid choice for \( f( 1_{\{ cyclic( 'm' ) \}} ) \) we need \( n \) to divide \( mF \). And if \( n \) does divide \( mF \), we check that \( (**) \) does satisfy the definition of ring homomorphisms.  Actually -- and this is important -- there are two things to check:

The dihedral group \( \{ dihedral( $n ) \} \) is generated by an element \(a\) of order \($n\), and an element \(b\) of order \(2\), satisfying the relation:    \((\ast)\)      \(ba = a^{n-1}b\)    (i) Determine number of group homomorphisms  \(f: \{ dihedral( $n ) \} \rightarrow \{ cyclic( $n ) \} \) with \(f(b)=0\).    \{ans_rule(10)\}    (ii) Determine the number of group homomorphisms \(g: \{ dihedral( $m ) \} \rightarrow \{ cyclic( $m ) \} \) with \(f(b)=$c\).     \{ans_rule(10)\}    Hint: Make use of the relation \((\ast)\).  END_TEXT   ANS(str_cmp($a1) ); ANS(str_cmp($a2) );   #Context()->texStrings; SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR SOLUTION $PAR Since \( \{ dihedral( n ) \} \) is generated by \(a\) and \(b\) and satisfies \(ba = a^{n-1}b\), a homomorphism from \( \{ dihedral( n ) \} \) to any group is determined by its values at \(a\) and at \(b\) provided that    \(f(a^n)=0\),    \(f(b^2)=0\), and    \(f(ba) = f(a^{n-1}b)\).  Using properties of homomorphisms, this becomes  (*1)   \(n f(a) = 0\),                   (*2)   \(2 f(b) = 0\), and  (*3)   \(f(b) + f(a) = (n-1)f(a) + f(b)\)  And since \( \{ cyclic( n ) \} \) is Abelian, this last condition plus (*1) means that  (*3')  \(2 f(a) = 0\).  Combine this with (*1) and we get  (*4)   \(\gcd(2, n) f(a) = 0\).

latex_expressions: ['\\(\\tan\\)', '\\(\\sec^3\\theta\\)', '\\(\\tan\\theta=\\frac{x}{$a}\\)', '\\(\\sec\\theta=\\frac{\\sqrt{$a2+x^2}}{$a}\\)', '\\(x/$a\\)', '\\(x\\)', '\\($a\\)', '\\(\\sqrt{$a2+x^2}\\)', '\\[ \\int x^2\\sqrt{$a2 + x^2}\\; dx \\]', '\\[x = {$a}\\tan(\\theta)\\]', '\\[dx = {$a}\\sec^2(\\theta) \\; d\\theta\\]', '\\[\\int x^2\\sqrt{$a2 + x^2} \\;dx=\\int $a2\\tan^2\\theta\\sqrt{$a2+$a2\\tan\\theta}($a\\sec^2\\theta) \\; d\\theta\\]', '\\[=\\int  $a4\\tan^2\\theta\\sec^3\\theta \\; d\\theta\\]', '\\[=$a4\\int  (\\sec^2\\theta-1)\\sec^3\\theta \\; d\\theta\\]', '\\[=$a4\\int  (\\sec^5\\theta-\\sec^3\\theta) \\; d\\theta\\]', '\\[\\int \\sec^n\\theta d\\theta=\\frac{1}{n-1}\\tan\\theta\\sec^{n-2}\\theta+\\frac{n-2}{n-1}\\int\\sec^{n-2}\\theta d\\theta.\\]', '\\[\\int\\sec^5\\theta d\\theta=\\frac{1}{5-1}\\tan\\theta\\sec^{5-2}\\theta+\\frac{5-2}{5-1}\\int\\sec^{5-2}\\theta d\\theta\\]', '\\[=\\frac{1}{4}\\tan\\theta\\sec^{3}\\theta+\\frac{3}{4}\\int\\sec^{3}\\theta d\\theta\\]', '\\[\\int\\sec^3\\theta d\\theta=\\frac{1}{3-1}\\tan\\theta\\sec^{3-2}\\theta+\\frac{3-2}{3-1}\\int\\sec^{3-2}\\theta d\\theta\\]', '\\[=\\frac{1}{2}\\tan\\theta\\sec\\theta+\\frac{1}{2}\\int\\sec\\theta d\\theta\\]']
question_text: END_TEXT ################################### # Main text BEGIN_TEXT Evaluate the indefinite integral. \[ \int x^2\sqrt{$a2 + x^2}\; dx \] \{ans_rule( 50) \} END_TEXT $ans = $funct; ANS( $funct->cmp() ); ################################## Context()->texStrings; ################################### TEXT($PAR, $BBOLD, $BITALIC, "Hi $studentLogin, If you don't get this in 5 tries I'll give you a hint with an applet to help you out.", $EITALIC, $EBOLD, $PAR); $im = image( "trigsub.png", width=>486, height=>306, tex_size=>900 ); $showHint=5; Context()->normalStrings; TEXT(hint( $PAR, MODES(TeX=>'object code', HTML=>$applet->insertAll( debug =>0, reinitialize_button => 0, includeAnswerBox=>0, ), TeX=>$im),"Follow the step-by-step questions in the hint in the online version of this problem." )); ################################## Context()->texStrings; SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $BBOLD Solution: $EBOLD $PAR To evaluate this integral use a trigonometric substitution. For this problem use the \(\tan\) substitution. \[x = {$a}\tan(\theta)\] So: \[dx = {$a}\sec^2(\theta) \; d\theta\] Therefore: \[\int x^2\sqrt{$a2 + x^2} \;dx=\int $a2\tan^2\theta\sqrt{$a2+$a2\tan\theta}($a\sec^2\theta) \; d\theta\] \[=\int $a4\tan^2\theta\sec^3\theta \; d\theta\] \[=$a4\int (\sec^2\theta-1)\sec^3\theta \; d\theta\] \[=$a4\int (\sec^5\theta-\sec^3\theta) \; d\theta\] Before proceeding to the several methods we can use to evaluate the integral of \(\sec^3\theta\), note that \(\tan\theta=\frac{x}{$a}\), and \(\sec\theta=\frac{\sqrt{$a2+x^2}}{$a}\). To see this, label a right triangle so that the tangent is \(x/$a\). We will have the opposite side with length \(x\), and the adjacent side with length \($a\), so the hypotenuse has length \(\sqrt{$a2+x^2}\). From this point, we apply the secant reduction formula to evaluate the integral. Use the secant reduction formula. The secant reduction formula is given by \[\int \sec^n\theta d\theta=\frac{1}{n-1}\tan\theta\sec^{n-2}\theta+\frac{n-2}{n-1}\int\sec^{n-2}\theta d\theta.\] so \[\int\sec^5\theta d\theta=\frac{1}{5-1}\tan\theta\sec^{5-2}\theta+\frac{5-2}{5-1}\int\sec^{5-2}\theta d\theta\] \[=\frac{1}{4}\tan\theta\sec^{3}\theta+\frac{3}{4}\int\sec^{3}\theta d\theta\] and \[\int\sec^3\theta d\theta=\frac{1}{3-1}\tan\theta\sec^{3-2}\theta+\frac{3-2}{3-1}\int\sec^{3-2}\theta d\theta\] \[=\frac{1}{2}\tan\theta\sec\theta+\frac{1}{2}\int\sec\theta d\theta\]

\{ beginproblem() \} \{ textbook_ref_exact("Rogawski ET 2e", "15.1","7") \} $PAR Let \(\mathcal{R} = [0,1] \times [0,1]\) .  Estimate \(\iint_{\mathcal{R}}$a (x+y)\,dA\) by computing two different Riemann sums, each with at least six rectangles. $PAR \(\iint_{\mathcal{R}}$a (x+y)\,dA\approx \) \{ans_rule()\} $PAR  END_TEXT Context()->flags->set(tolerance=>.1); ANS($answer->cmp);  Context()->texStrings;  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR $SOL We define the following subrectangles and sample points: $PAR \{image("image_15_1_7.png", width=>390, height=>214)\}  The sample points defined in the two figures are:  \((\mathbf{A})\) \[ \begin{array}{lll}{P}_{11}=\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)&{P}_{21}=\left(\frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{4}\right)&{P}_{31}=( 1,0 )\\ \noalign{\smallskip} {P}_{12}=\left(\frac{1}{3},\frac{3}{4}\right)&{P}_{22}=\left(\frac{1}{2},1\right)&{P}_{32}=\left(\frac{5}{6},\frac{3}{4}\right)\end{array} \] \((\mathbf{B})\) \[ \begin{array}{lll}{P}_{11}=\left(\frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{3}\right)&{P}_{21}=\left(\frac{3}{4},\frac{1}{6}\right)&{P}_{12}=\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)\\ \noalign{\smallskip} {P}_{22}=\left(1,\frac{2}{3}\right)&{P}_{13}=\left(\frac{1}{4},\frac{5}{6}\right)&{P}_{23}=\left(\frac{3}{4},\frac{5}{6}\right)\end{array} \] We compute the values of \(f( x,y )=$a(x+y)\) at the sample points: \((\mathbf{A})\) \[f\left({P}_{11}\right)=f\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)=$a\left(0+\frac{1}{2}\right)=$a\cdot\frac{1}{2}\] \[f\left({P}_{21}\right)=f\left(\frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{4}\right)=$a\left(\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{4}\right)=$a\cdot\frac{3}{4}\] \[f\left({P}_{31}\right)=f( 1,0 )=$a(1+0)=$a\] \[f\left({P}_{12}\right)=f\left(\frac{1}{3},\frac{3}{4}\right)=$a\left(\frac{1}{3}+\frac{3}{4}\right)=$a\cdot\frac{13}{12}\] \[f\left({P}_{22}\right)=f\left(\frac{1}{2},1\right)=$a\left(\frac{1}{2}+1\right)=$a\cdot\frac{3}{2}\] \[f\left({P}_{32}\right)=f\left(\frac{5}{6},\frac{3}{4}\right)=$a\left(\frac{5}{6}+\frac{3}{4}\right)=$a\cdot\frac{19}{12}\] Each subrectangle has sides of length \(\Delta x=\frac{1}{3}, \Delta y=\frac{1}{2}\) and area \(\Delta A=\Delta x\Delta y=\frac{1}{3}\cdot \frac{1}{2}=\frac{1}{6}\).  We obtain the following Riemann sum: \[{S}_{32} = \sum_{i=1}^3\sum_{j=1}^2f\left({P}_{ij}\right)\Delta A=\]\[ \frac{$a}{6}\left(\frac{1}{2}+\frac{3}{4}+1+\frac{13}{12}+\frac{3}{2}+\frac{19}{12}\right)= \frac{$a\cdot 77}{72}\approx $sol1\]  \((\mathbf{B})\)  \[f\left({P}_{11}\right)=f\left(\frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{3}\right)=$a\left(\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{3}\right)=$a\cdot\frac{5}{6}\] \[f\left({P}_{21}\right)=f\left(\frac{3}{4},\frac{1}{6}\right)=$a\left(\frac{3}{4}+\frac{1}{6}\right)=$a\cdot\frac{11}{12}\] \[f\left({P}_{12}\right)=f\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)=$a\left(0+\frac{1}{2}\right)=$a\cdot\frac{1}{2}\] \[f\left({P}_{22}\right)=f\left(1,\frac{2}{3}\right)=$a\left(1+\frac{2}{3}\right)=$a\cdot\frac{5}{3}\] \[f\left({P}_{13}\right)=f\left(\frac{1}{4},\frac{5}{6}\right)=$a\left(\frac{1}{4}+\frac{5}{6}\right)=$a\cdot\frac{13}{12}\] \[f\left({P}_{23}\right)=f\left(\frac{3}{4},\frac{5}{6}\right)=$a\left(\frac{3}{4}+\frac{5}{6}\right)=$a\cdot\frac{19}{12}\] Each subrectangle has sides of length \(\Delta x=\frac{1}{2}, \Delta y=\frac{1}{3}\)

Use \{htmlLink("http://www.math.utah.edu/online/1010/working/", "long division")\} to divide these two polynomials with remainder:      \(2x^4+11x^3+19x^2+x-29 = (x^2+4x+6)\times(\)   \{ ans_rule(15) \} \( ) + ( \) EOT ANS(fun_cmp("2*x**2+3*x-5", limits=>[[-5,-1]], vars=>["x"])); TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \{ ans_rule(15) \} \( ) \) EOT ANS(fun_cmp("3*x+1", limits=>[[-5,-1]], vars=>["x"]));       SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));   $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD Long division gives: \[ \begin{array}{rrrrrrrrr} &&&&&&2x^2 &+ 3 x &- 5\\ &&&&&&&&\\ x^2 &+ 4x &+ 6 &\big| &2x^4 &+ 11x^3 &+ 19x^2 &+ x &- 29\\     &     &    &       &2x^4 &+ 8x^3  &+ 12x^2&& \\ &&&&&&&&\\ &&&&& 3x^3 &+ 7 x^2&+ x &- 29 \\  &&&&& 3x^3 &+ 12 x^2 &+ 18x &  \\  &&&&&&&&\\ &&&&&&- 5x ^2 &- 17 x &- 29 \\ &&&&&&- 5x ^2 &- 20 x &- 30 \\ &&&&&&&&\\ &&&&&&&3x &+ 1 \\ \end{array} \]  Thus  \[2x^4+11x^3+19x^2+x-29 = (x^2+4x+6)\times(2x^2+3x-5)+3x+1.\]

question_text: A stone is thrown straight up from the edge of a roof, \( $s1 \)  feet above the ground, at a speed of \($v1\) feet per second.   $BBOLD A. $EBOLD Remembering that the acceleration due to gravity is  \(-32 \textrm{ft}/\textrm{sec}^2\), how high is the stone \($t1\) seconds later?   Answer: \{ans_rule(30) \} feet.    $BBOLD B. $EBOLD At what time does the stone hit the ground?   Answer: \{ans_rule(30) \} sec   $BBOLD C. $EBOLD What is the velocity of the stone when it hits the ground?   Answer: \{ans_rule(30) \} ft/sec.   END_TEXT  $ans1 =  "-16*$t1^2 + $v1*$t1 + $s1"; $ans2 = "($v1 + sqrt( $v1*$v1+64*$s1))/32";  $t2=($v1 + sqrt( $v1*$v1+64*$s1))/32; $ans3 =  "-(32*$t2) + $v1";  ANS(num_cmp($ans1)); ANS(num_cmp($ans2)); ANS(num_cmp($ans3));  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOF')); $SOL  To solve this problem, one must remember the relationship between position at time \( t \) (\( s(t) \)), instantaneous velocity at time \( t \) (\( v(t) \)), and acceleration at time \( t\) (\(a(t)\)). This relationship is given by:  \[   \begin{array}     v(t)  = s'(t) \\     a(t)  = v'(t) = s''(t) \\   \end{array} \]  With this in mind, this problem becomes an exercise in finding antideriviatives.  We are told that the the acceleration due to gravity  is -32 feet per second squared, so that the function \( a(t) = -32 \).   Throughout this problem, it is important to remember which way is up.  That  is, negative values mean the object is accelerating or moving down, positive  values mean it is accelerating or moving up.  With this in mind, we need to compute the formula for the velocity of the stone at time \( t \).  Since the acceleration function is \( a(t) = -32 \), the velocity function is the general antiderivative of this, or \( v(t) = -32t + C_1 \) where \( C_1 \) is a  constant.  We are told that the initial speed of the stone is $v1 feet per second. Therefore, \( v(0) = -32(0) + C_1 = $v1 \Rightarrow C_1 = $v1 \).  Hence, the  formula for the instantaneous velocity at time \( t \) is \( v(t) = -32t+$v1 \).  Finally, we need to find a formula for the position of the stone at time \( t \). Taking the antiderivative of the velocity, we get \( s(t) = -16t^2+{$v1}t+C_2 \)  where \( C_2 \) is again an unknown constant.  However, we are told that the height  of the building, and thus the initial height of the stone (we can assume that the  person doing the throwing is arbitrarily short) is $s1 feet.  Therefore,  \( s(0) = -16(0)^2 + {$v1}(0) + C_2 = $s1 \Rightarrow C_2 = $s1 \).  And, our  formula for position at time \(t\) is \(s(t) = -16t^2+{$v1}t+$s1 \).  Putting this all to gether to answer the three questions posed, we get the following answers:  \[   \begin{array}     \mbox{A. } s($t1)  = -16($t1)^2 + {$v1}($t1) + $s1 = $ans1 \\     \\     \mbox{B. } s(t)  = -16t^2 + {$v1}t + $s1 = 0 \\               t  = \frac{-$v1 - \sqrt{($v1)^2-4(-16)($s1)}}{2(-16)} \\                  = $ans2 \\     \\     \mbox{C. } v($ans2)  = -32($ans2) + $v1 \\                         = $ans3 \\   \end{array} \]

Find the area of the region enclosed by the parametric equation  \[ x =  t^3 - $a t \] \[ y = $b t^2  \] \{ans_rule(20)\} EOT  $answer = 8*$b*$a**(5/2)/15; ANS(num_cmp($answer));  $b1 = 2 * $b; $y1 = $b * $a;  &SOLUTION(EV2(<<EOT)); $SOL  First, graph the function by plotting various values of t.  You should notice that \( t = \sqrt {$a} \) and \( t = -\sqrt {$a} \) yields the same x and y coordinates, namely (0,$y1).  These two values of t are going to be the upper and lower limits of integration.  The area under a curve defined by parameters \( x = f(t) \) and \( y = g(t) \) can be expressed \[ A = \int ydx =\int g(t)f'(t)dt \] Plugging in the functions and the upper and lower limits of integration, we have \[ A = \int_{-\sqrt{$a}}^{\sqrt{$a}} $b t^2 (3 t^2 - $a) dt \] \[    = (2) ($b) \int_{0}^{\sqrt{$a}} (3 t^4 - $a t^2) dt \] \[    = $b1 \left[ \frac {3}{5} t^5 - \frac {$a}{3} t^3                             \right]_{0}^{\sqrt{$a}} \] \[    = $b1 \left[ \frac {3}{5} $a^{5/2} - \frac {$a}{3} $a^{3/2}                             \right] \] \[    = $answer \]

\(\frac{1}{x^2+$a2 x+$as} +\frac{1}{x+$a}  =( \)  \{ ans_rule(15) \} \()/( \) EOT ANS(fun_cmp("x+$a+1", vars=>["x"])); TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \{ ans_rule(15) \} \( ) \). EOT ANS(fun_cmp("(x+$a)**2", limits=>[[-5,-1]], vars=>["x"]));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \(\frac{1}{x^2+$a2 x+$as}-\frac{1}{x+$a} =( \)  \{ ans_rule(15) \} \()/( \) EOT ANS(fun_cmp("-(x+$a-1)", vars=>["x"])); TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \{ ans_rule(15) \} \( ) \). EOT ANS(fun_cmp("(x+$a)**2", limits=>[[-5,-1]], vars=>["x"]));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \( \frac{1}{x^2+$a2 x+$as}\times \frac{1}{x+$a} =( \)  \{ ans_rule(15) \} \()/( \) EOT ANS(fun_cmp(" 1 ", vars=>["x"])); TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \{ ans_rule(15) \} \( ) \). EOT ANS(fun_cmp("(x+$a)**3", limits=>[[-5,-1]], vars=>["x"]));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \(\frac{1}{x^2+$a2 x+$as}\div\frac{1}{x+$a} =( \)  \{ ans_rule(15) \} \()/( \) EOT ANS(fun_cmp("1", limits=>[[-5,-1]], vars=>["x"])); TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \{ ans_rule(15) \} \( ) \). EOT ANS(fun_cmp(" x+$a ", vars=>["x"]));        TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  Hint:  Think about the \{htmlLink("http://www.math.utah.edu/online/1010/binom/", "binomial formulas")\} EOT  $ap1 = $a + 1; $am1 = $a - 1;  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD By the binomial formula, \[x^2+$a2 x+$as = (x+$a)^2.\] Hence     \[ \begin{array}{rcccccl} \frac{1}{x^2+$a2 x+$as} + \frac{1}{x+$a}     &=& \frac{1}{(x+$a)(x+$a)} +\frac{1}{x+$a}     &=& \frac{1+x+$a}{(x+$a)(x+$a)}     &=& \frac{x+$ap1}{(x+$a)^2} \\ \\ \frac{1}{x^2+$a2 x+$as} - \frac{1}{x+$a}     &=& \frac{1}{(x+$a)(x+$a)} -\frac{1}{x+$a}     &=& \frac{1-(x+$a)}{(x+$a)(x+$a)}     &=& \frac{-x -$am1}{(x+$a)^2} \\ \\ \frac{1}{x^2+$a2 x+$as} \times \frac{1}{x+$a}     &=& \frac{1}{(x+$a)(x+$a)} \times \frac{1}{x+$a}     &=& \frac{1}{(x+$a)(x+$a)^2}     &=& \frac{1}{(x+$a)^3} \\ \\ \frac{1}{x^2+$a2 x+$as} \div \frac{1}{x+$a}     &=& \frac{1}{(x+$a)(x+$a)} \times \frac{x+$a}{1}     &&&=& \frac{1}{x+$a} \end{array} \]

The period of a simple pendulum of length \(L\) feet is given by \[T=2\pi \sqrt{\frac{L}{g}} \hbox{~seconds.}\] We assume that \(g\), the acceleration due to gravity on the surface of the earth, is 32 feet per second per second.  If the pendulum is that of a clock that keeps good time when \(L = 4\) feet, how much time will the clock gain in 24 hours if the length of the pendulum is decreased to 3.97 feet?  (Use differentials and evaluate the necessary derivative at \(L=4\) feet.)   Your answer: \{&ans_rule(5)\} seconds. EOT ANS(num_cmp(324));    SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));   $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD Note that there are \(24\times 60\times 60 = 86,400 \) seconds in a day. Let \[T(L) = 2\pi \sqrt{\frac{L}{g}} = 2\pi \left(\frac{L}{g}\right)^{1/2}.\] Then \[T'(L) = \pi \left(\frac{L}{g}\right)^{-1/2} \times \frac{1}{g}.\] The  approximate time discrepancy is \[\frac{T'(4)(4-3.97)}{T(4)}\times 86,400 = 324 \hbox{~seconds.}\]

Evaluate the integral \[ \int_{0}^{$a} \frac{dx}{\sqrt{1-x^2}} \]  \{ans_rule( 20)\} EOT  $answer=arcsin($a)-arcsin(0); ANS(num_cmp($answer));  &SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT')); $SOL  Our first step is to find the antiderivative of \( \frac{dx}{\sqrt{1-x^2}} \).  The best way to do this is to use the integration tables available in the back of your book.  Notice that this integral has a form similar to the entry below, taken from your tables: $PAR \[   \int \frac{du}{\sqrt{a^2-u^2}} = \sin^{-1} \frac{u}{a} + C \] In our case, \( a = 1 \) and \( u = x \).  Therefore, our antiderivative is: \[   F(x) = \left(\sin^{-1} x \right) + C \] Then, applying the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, and using a calculator to compute, we get: \[   \begin{aligned}     \int_0^{$a} \frac{dx}{\sqrt{1-x^2}} dx &= F($a) - F(0) \\     &= \left(\sin^{-1} $a\right) + C -        \left(\sin^{-1} 0\right) - C\\     &= !{$answer:%5.4f}   \end{aligned} \]
