Let \(p\) be the quartic (degree 4) polynomial that satisfies \[p(i) = 2^i,\quad i = 0,1,2,3,4.\] Then   \(p(x) = \)  \{ ans_rule(40) \}.  EOT    ANS(fun_cmp("(x**4 - 2*x**3 + 11*x**2 + 14*x + 24)/24", limits=>[[0,5]], vars=>["x"]));  TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Hint: $EBOLD  You may have a better idea, but a brute force approach is to write  \[p(x) = ax^4 + bx^3 + cx^2 + dx + e\]  where \(a\), \(b\), \(c\), \(d\), and \(e\), are the unknown coefficients, and then solve the linear system \(p(0) = 1\), \(p(1) = 2\), \(p(2) = 4\), \(p(3) = 8\), and \(p(4) = 16\) for \(a\), \(b\), \(c\), \(d\), and \(e\). EOT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));   $BBOLD Solution: $EBOLD Proceeding as suggested in the hint gives the linear system  \[ \begin{array}{llllllllllllll}   &  &  &  & e &= 1 \\ a &+ b &+ c &+ d &+ e &= 2 \\ 16a &+ 8b &+ 4c &+ 2d &+ e &= 4 \\ 81a &+ 27b &+ 9c &+ 3d &+ e &= 8 \\ 256a &+ 64b &+ 16c &+ 4d &+ e &= 16 \\ \end{array} \]  This is a system of five equations in five unknowns, but of course \(e\) is given explicitly in the first equations, and so we really only have to solve four equations in four unknowns.  The solution of this problem is \[a=\frac{1}{24}, b = -\frac{1}{12}, c =  \frac{11}{24}, d=\frac{7}{12}, e=1.\]      Here is another, more complicated looking, but actually much  simpler, approach:  Write  \( p(x) = A + Bx + Cx(x-1) + Dx(x-1)(x-2) + Ex(x-1)(x-2)(x-3).\) Then we get the $BBOLD triangular$EBOLD linear system \[ \begin{array}{llllllll} p(0) &= A &  &  &  &    &= 1 \\ p(1) &= A &+ B &  &  &    &= 2 \\ p(2) &= A &+ 2B &+ 2C &  &    &= 4 \\ p(3) &= A &+ 3B &+ 6C &+ 6D   &  &= 8 \\ p(4) &= A &+ 4B &+ 12C &+ 24D &  + 24E &=16 \\ \end{array} \]  This system requires no elimination at all, just  (in this case $BBOLD forward $EBOLD) substitution.  The first equations tells us that \(A=1\).   Substituting in the second equation and solving for \(B\) gives  \(B=1\), the third equation gives \(C=1/2\), the fourth \(D=1/6\),  and the last \(E=1/24\). Thus  \( p(x) = 1 + x + \frac{1}{2}x(x-1) + \frac{1}{6}x(x-1)(x-2) +  \frac{1}{24}x(x-1)(x-2)(x-3).\) You can of course convert this polynomial to standard form  but you can also just enter it as \( 1+x+1/2x(x-1)+1/6x(x-1)(x-2)+1/24x(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)\)

Each person tries to balance his or her time between leisure and work. The tradeoff is that as you work less your income falls.  Therefore each person has ${BITALIC}indifference curves$EITALIC which connect the number of hours of leisure, \( l \), and income, \( s \).  If, for example, you are indifferent between 0 hours of leisure and an income of ${DOLLAR}1125  a week on the one hand, and 10 hours of leisure and an income of  ${DOLLAR}750 a week on the other hand, then the points \( l=0 \), \( s=1125 \), and \( l=10 \), \( s=750 \) both lie on the same indifference curve. $PAR The table below gives information on three indifference curves, I, II, and III. $PAR $tstart $tbody $tend $PAR ${BBOLD}(a)$EBOLD On a sheet of paper, or using a calculator or other technology, graph the three indifference curves. Recall that to find the cost to produce the nth unit in a production process, we calculate the difference  \[ C(n-1) - C(n) .\]   This works well when do a small production run. However suppose we wanted  to talk about the costs associated with large or long runs. Take the  popular hamburger franchise with golden arches. The total cost (in dollars)  of producing \(x\) million hamburgers might be    \[ C(x) = $a + $b x - $c x^2. \]   (A) Find the exact cost of producing the 2,000,001st burger. Be careful  though. The units for \(x\) are millions of units. The 2,000,001st  burger is represented by 2.000001!   Exact cost of 2,000,001st burger = \{ans_rule(75) \}   EOT  $ans = ($a + $b*2.001 - $c*((2.000001)**2)) - ($a + $b*2.000 - $c*((2.000000)**2)); ANS(num_cmp($ans));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); (B) Use marginal cost to approximate the cost of producing the 2000001st burger.   Approx. cost of 2000001st burger = \{ans_rule(75) \}

\{ textbook_ref_exact("Rogawski ET 2e", "16.3","1") \} $PAR Verify that \($FF=\nabla\varphi\) and evaluate the line integral of \($FF\) over the given path: $PAR \( $FF = \left<$fx,$fy\right> \) , \(\quad \varphi(x,y)=$phitex\) ;   Upper half of a circle with radius \($r\), centered at the origin and oriented counterclockwise $PAR Answer : \{ans_rule()\} $PAR   END_TEXT  Context()->normalStrings; ANS($answer->cmp);  Context()->texStrings; SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR $SOL We compute the gradient of \(\varphi ( x,y )=$phitex\): \[\nabla \varphi = \left< \frac{\partial \varphi }{\partial x},\frac{\partial \varphi }{\partial y} \right> = \left< $fx, $fy \right> =$FF  \]  We now use the Fundamental Theorem of Gradient Vector Fields.  The terminal point is \(Q=( -$r,0 )\) and the initial point is \(P=( $r,0 )\), therefore: \[\int_{\mathbf{c}} $FF \cdot d\mathbf{s}  = \varphi (Q)-\varphi (P)= \]\[ \varphi ( -$r,0 )-\varphi ( $r,0 )= \frac1{$deg}\cdot (-$r)^{$deg}\cdot 0^{$deg}-\frac1{$deg}\cdot $r^{$deg}\cdot 0^{$deg} = $answer \]

You and your friend part at an intersection.  Your friend drives away north at a constant speed. You linger at the intersection for an hour, and then drive off due east at a speed that is $d miles per hour faster than your friend's speed. Two hours after your friend's departure the distance between the two of you is $D miles.  $t hours after your friend's departure your distance from your friend is \{ ans_rule(15) \} miles.  (Remember that ww expects your answer to be within one tenth of one percent of the true answer.) EOT ANS(num_cmp($ans));   SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));   $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD We can work out your friend's speed as in the preceding problem.  It is $v mph.  Hence you are traveling at $V mph. In those $t hours, your friend travels \($t\times $v = $tv\) miles, and you travel \(($t-1)\times$V = $TV\) miles.  By the Pythagorean Theorem, the distance \(d\) between you and your friend is \[d = \sqrt{$tv^2 + $TV^2} \approx $m \hbox{~miles}.\]

latex_expressions: ['\\( \\displaystyle f(x) =  \\int_x^{x^{$b1}} t^{$a1}dt \\)', "\\( f'(x) = \\)", '\\(g(x)\\)', '\\(x\\)', '\\(\\frac{d}{dx} g(x)\\)', "\\(g'(x)\\)", '\\(f(x)\\)', '\\(x\\)', '\\(x\\)', '\\[ g(x) = \\int_a^x f(t) dt \\]', '\\[ \\frac{d}{dx} \\int_0^u f(t) dt \t= \\frac{d}{du} \\left( \\int_0^u f(t) dt \\right) \\frac{du}{dx} \t= f(u) \\frac{du}{dx} \\]', "\\[ \\begin{aligned} f'(x)   &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\left( \\int_x^{x^{$b1}} t^{$a1} dt \\right)  \\\\\\\\         &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\left( \\int_0^{x^{$b1}} t^{$a1} dt \t\t+ \\int_x^0 t^{$a1} dt \\right)\t\\\\\\\\         &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\left( \\int_0^{x^{$b1}} t^{$a1} dt \\right) \t\t+ \\frac{d}{dx} \\left( \\int_x^0 t^{$a1} dt \\right)\t\\\\\\\\         &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\left( \\int_0^{x^{$b1}} t^{$a1} dt \\right) \t\t- \\frac{d}{dx} \\left( \\int_0^x t^{$a1} dt \\right)\t\\\\\\\\ \t&= \\left(x^{$b1}\\right)^{$a1} \\left($b1 x^{$soln_b1m1}\\right) \t\t- x^{$a1}\t\\\\\\\\ \t&  \\hspace{0.5cm} \\text{The left expression obtained by Fact 2}\t\\\\\\\\ \t&  \\hspace{0.5cm} \\text{above, and the right by Fact 1}\t\\\\\\\\ \t&= $b1 x^{$e1} - x^{$a1} \\end{aligned} \\]"]
question_text: If \( \displaystyle f(x) =  \int_x^{x^{$b1}} t^{$a1}dt \) $PAR then  \( f'(x) = \) \{ans_rule(30)\} $PAR EOT  $ans1="$b1*x^$e1 -  x^$a1";  ANS(fun_cmp($ans1));  $soln_b1m1 = $b1 - 1;  &SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $SOL    The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, part I, can be found on p.392 of your textbook.  It says that if \[ g(x) = \int_a^x f(t) dt \] then the derivative of \(g(x)\) with respect to \(x\), written \(\frac{d}{dx} g(x)\) or \(g'(x)\), is equal to \(f(x)\).  Call this "Fact 1" so that we can refer to it below.  $PAR  Then on p.395, in example 3, we learn that we must use the chain rule if the upper limit on the integral is not simply \(x\), but a function of \(x\): \[ \frac{d}{dx} \int_0^u f(t) dt 	= \frac{d}{du} \left( \int_0^u f(t) dt \right) \frac{du}{dx} 	= f(u) \frac{du}{dx} \] Call this "Fact 2" so that we can refer to it below.  $PAR   Applying that in this particular circumstance, we find \[ \begin{aligned} f'(x)   &= \frac{d}{dx} \left( \int_x^{x^{$b1}} t^{$a1} dt \right)  \\\\         &= \frac{d}{dx} \left( \int_0^{x^{$b1}} t^{$a1} dt 		+ \int_x^0 t^{$a1} dt \right)	\\\\         &= \frac{d}{dx} \left( \int_0^{x^{$b1}} t^{$a1} dt \right) 		+ \frac{d}{dx} \left( \int_x^0 t^{$a1} dt \right)	\\\\         &= \frac{d}{dx} \left( \int_0^{x^{$b1}} t^{$a1} dt \right) 		- \frac{d}{dx} \left( \int_0^x t^{$a1} dt \right)	\\\\ 	&= \left(x^{$b1}\right)^{$a1} \left($b1 x^{$soln_b1m1}\right) 		- x^{$a1}	\\\\ 	&  \hspace{0.5cm} \text{The left expression obtained by Fact 2}	\\\\ 	&  \hspace{0.5cm} \text{above, and the right by Fact 1}	\\\\ 	&= $b1 x^{$e1} - x^{$a1} \end{aligned} \]

You are flying a kite on a line that is \(350\) feet long.  Let's suppose the line is perfectly straight (it never really is) and it makes an angle of \(65\) degrees with the horizontal direction.  The kite is flying at an altitude of \{ ans_rule(21) \} feet. EOT     ANS(num_cmp(317.2077));  TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Hint:$EBOLD  Draw a picture.  Look for a right triangle. EOT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));   $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD Consider the right triangle formed by your position, the kite, and the line vertically down from the kite to the ground. Let \(h\) denote the unknown height of the kite.  Then  \[\sin(65^\circ) = \frac{h}{350},\] i.e., \[h = 350 \times \sin(65^\circ) \approx 317.2 \hbox{~feet}.\]

$PAR Let \[ f(x)  = \begin{cases}                0 & \text{if } x < $p1 \\               $a& \text{if } $p1 \leq x < $p3 \\               $b& \text{if } $p3 \leq x < $p5 \\               0 & \text{if } x \geq $p5 \end{cases} \] and \[ g(x)  = \int_{$p1}^{x} f(t) dt \]  Determine the value of each of the following:  (a) \( g($p0) = \) \{ans_rule(5)\}  (b) \( g($p2) = \) \{ans_rule(5)\}  (c) \( g($p4) = \) \{ans_rule(5)\}  (d) \( g($p6) = \) \{ans_rule(5)\}  (e) The absolute maximum of \( g(x) \) occurs when \( x = \) \{ans_rule(5)\} and is the value \{ans_rule(5)\}  $PAR It may be helpful to make a graph of \(f(x)\) when answering these questions. EOT  $ans1 = 0; $ans2 = $a; $ans3 = $a * ($p3 - $p1) + $b; $ans4 = $a * ($p3 - $p1) + $b * ($p5 - $p3); $ans5 = $p3; $ans6 = $a * ($p3 - $p1);  ANS(num_cmp($ans1)); ANS(num_cmp($ans2)); ANS(num_cmp($ans3)); ANS(num_cmp($ans4)); ANS(num_cmp($ans5)); ANS(num_cmp($ans6));  $np = $r2-1;  $graph = init_graph($r2-1,-6,7,6,'axes'=>[0,0],'grid'=>[8-$r2,12],'size'=>[500,500]); plot_functions($graph,   FEQ("0 for x in [$np,$p1] using color=blue and weight=2"),   FEQ("$a for x in [$p1,$p3] using color=blue and weight=2"),   FEQ("$b for x in [$p3,$p5] using color=blue and weight=2"),   FEQ("0 for x in [$p5,7] using color=blue and weight=2") ); $my_txt = image(insertGraph($graph));  &SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT')); $SOL  As the problem statement suggests, the best method to use in solving this problem is to graph the function \( f(x) \).  Then, we can use the fact that the integration of a curve on the interval [a,b] can be  interpreted as the area underneath that curve between the lines \(x=a\) and \(x=b\). $PAR  The graph of \( f(x) \) is shown below (Click on it to enlarge). $PAR  $my_txt $PAR   (a) \( g($p0) \) will be the area under the graph of \( f(x) \) for   \( $p0 \leq x \leq $p1 \).  As \( f \) is always 0 on that   interval in the graph, the area underneath it is clearly   0, making \( g($p0) = 0 \). $PAR   (b) In this case, we want the area underneath the graph of \( f(x) \)   on the interval \( $p1 \leq x \leq $p2 \).  On this interval, \( f \)   is always $a.  Therefore, the value of \( g($p0) \) is   \{ ($p2-$p1)*$a \}. $PAR   (c) To compute \( g($p4) \), note that \( f \) takes on two different   values on the interval [$p1,$p4].  Between $p1 and $p3, \(f\) has the   value $a.  Between $p3 and $p4, \( f \) has the value $b.  Therefore,   the value of \( g($p4) \) is \( $a($p3-$p1) + $b($p4-$p3) = $ans3 \). $PAR   (d) In computing \( g($p6) \), we note that again, \( f \) takes on   different values on the interval [$p1,$p6].  Between $p1 and $p3, the   value is $a.  Between $p3 and $p4 the value is $b.  Finally, between   $p4 and $p6, the value is 0.  Hence, the value of   \( g($p6) \) is \( $a($p3-$p1) + $b($p5-$p3) + 0($p6-$p5) = $ans4 \). $PAR   (e) The maximum value of \( g \) occurs at the \( x \) for which   \( f \) has the largest area between $p1 and \( x \).  Note   that between $p3 and $p5, \( f \) actually has a negative   value, which would take away from the value of \( g \).  Therefore,   the maximum value will take place at $p3.  That value will be   the total area underneath the graph between $p1 and $p3,    which is $ans6. $PAR

question_text: Use implicit differentiation to find the points where the $BBOLD parabola $EBOLD defined by  \[ $f = 0 \] has horizontal and vertical tangent lines.   The parabola has horizontal tangent lines at the \{ helpLink(point, "point(s)") \} \{ ans_rule(15) \}.   The parabola has vertical tangent lines at the point(s) \{ ans_rule(15) \}. END_TEXT Context()->normalStrings; #####################################################################  ANS($ans1->cmp()); ANS($ans2->cmp());  Context('Numeric')->variables->are( 	x => 'Real', 	y => 'Real', 	dydx => [ 'Real', TeX => '\, \frac{dy}{dx}' ] );  $amb = $a - $b; $ambm2 = $a - $b - 2; $amb2p4b = ($a - $b)**2 + 4*$b; $fb = 4*$b; $ft1pb = 4*(1 + $b);  $f_revised = Formula( 	"(x - y)^2 - 2*($amb)*(x - y) + $amb2p4b - 4*y" )->reduce; $mfx = Formula("y - x + $amb")->reduce; $fy = Formula("y - x + $ambm2")->reduce; $df = Formula( 	"2*x - 2*y - 2*x*dydx + 2*y*dydx 	- 2*$amb + 2*$ambm2*dydx" )->reduce;   Context()->texStrings; BEGIN_SOLUTION Differentiating implicitly with respect to \( x \) gives \[ $df = 0, \] or \[ ($fy) \, \frac{dy}{dx} = $mfx, \] and so \[ \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{$mfx}{$fy}. \] The tangent line to the parabola is horizontal where \( \frac{dy}{dx} = 0 \), i.e., where \( x - y = $amb \).  The equation of the parabola can be written in the form \[ $f_revised = 0, \] and \( x - y = $amb \) gives \( $fb = 4y \), or \( y = $b \), and \( x = $a \). Hence, the tangent line to the parabola is horizontal at the point \( $ans1 \) and nowhere else.

Einstein's Special Theory of Relativity says that the mass \(m\) of an object moving at a velocity \(v\) is given by the formula \[m = \frac{m_0}{\sqrt{1-v^2/c^2}}=m_0\left(1-\frac{v^2}{c^2}\right)^{-1/2}.\] Here \(m_0\) is the rest mass (mass at velocity 0) and \(c\) is the velocity of light. Use differentials to estimate the percentage increase of the object as its velocity increases from \(v=0.94c\) to \(0.95c\).  Evaluate the necessary derivative at \(v=0.94c\).   Your answer: \{&ans_rule(5)\} percent. EOT ANS(num_cmp(8.07,reltol => 1));    SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));   $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD Let \[m(v) = m_0\left(1-\frac{v^2}{c^2}\right)^{-1/2}.\] Then \[m'(v) = -\frac{m_0}{2}\left(1-\frac{v^2}{c^2}\right)^{-3/2}\times \left(-\frac{2v}{c^2}\right)= \frac{m_0 v}{c^2} \left(1-\frac{v^2}{c^2}\right)^{-3/2}.\] We want to compute \[p = \frac{100\times w'(0.94)\times (0.95-0.94) }{w(0.94)}\approx 8.08 \char37.\]   Note: Since we are computing a percentage the value of the rest mass \(m_0\) does not matter.  We could simply set it equal to 1.

The Great Pyramid of Cheops has a square base with a length of 756 feet.  Its height is 482 feet.  If you walk straight up from the center of the north side to the top of the pyramid you have to climb an angle of  \{ ans_rule(12) \} degrees. EOT  $pi=2.0*acos(0.0); ANS(num_cmp(atan(482/378)/$pi*180));   TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  You decide to simplify your life and walk up along one of the ridges. Thus you have to climb only at an angle of  \{ ans_rule(12) \} degrees. EOT  ANS(num_cmp(atan(482/378/sqrt(2))/$pi*180));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  On your way up the ridge you walk a distance of   \{ ans_rule(12) \} feet. EOT  ANS(num_cmp(sqrt(482**2+756**2/2)));    TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Hint:$EBOLD  For the first two parts draw right triangles and use an inverse trig function.  For the third part just use the Pythagorean Theorem.  EOT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));   $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD For the first part consider the right triangle formed by your starting point, the tip of the pyramid, and the point directly underneath the tip on the base of the pyramid. The vertical edge of that triangle forms the the height of the pyramid and has a length of 482 feet.  The horizontal edge of that triangle has a length that equals half the length of the base of the pyramid, i.e., 378 feet.  Thus your climbing angle is \[\arctan\left(\frac{482}{378}\right) \approx 51.90^\circ.\] If you start  in a corner of the base you get another triangle with the same vertical edge, but a horizontal edge of length \(\sqrt{378^2+378^2}\). Thus the corresponding angle is  \[\arctan\left(\frac{482}{\sqrt{378^2+378^2}}\right) \approx  42.04^\circ.\] The length \(L\) of the ridge going to the top can be obtained by applying the Pythagorean Theorem twice.  It is \[L = \sqrt{378^2+378^2+482^2} \approx 719.8 \quad \hbox{feet}\]

Calculating the flux through each face separately, we have:  On \( x = $x1 \), \( \int_S\vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_a^b\int_c^d\) \{ ans_rule(15) \} \(dz\,dy\) = \{ ans_rule(15) \}  where \(a = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}, \(b = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}, \(c = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \} and \(d = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}.  $PAR On \( x = $x0 \), \( \int_S\vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_a^b\int_c^d\) \{ ans_rule(15) \} \(dz\,dy\) = \{ ans_rule(15) \}  where \(a = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}, \(b = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}, \(c = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \} and \(d = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}.  $PAR On \( y = $y1 \), \( \int_S\vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_a^b\int_c^d\) \{ ans_rule(15) \} \(dz\,dx\) = \{ ans_rule(15) \}  where \(a = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}, \(b = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}, \(c = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \} and \(d = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}.  $PAR On \( y = $y0 \), \( \int_S\vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_a^b\int_c^d\) \{ ans_rule(15) \} \(dz\,dx\) = \{ ans_rule(15) \}  where \(a = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}, \(b = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}, \(c = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \} and \(d = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}.  $PAR On \( z = $z1 \), \( \int_S\vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_a^b\int_c^d\) \{ ans_rule(15) \} \(dy\,dx\) = \{ ans_rule(15) \}  where \(a = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}, \(b = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}, \(c = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \} and \(d = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}.  $PAR And on \( z = $z0 \), \( \int_S\vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_a^b\int_c^d\) \{ ans_rule(15) \} \(dy\,dx\) = \{ ans_rule(15) \}  where \(a = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}, \(b = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}, \(c = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \} and \(d = \)\{ ans_rule(5) \}.  $PAR Thus, summing these, we have \(\int_S\vec F\cdot d\vec A =\)\{ans_rule(25)\}  END_TEXT Context()->normalStrings;  $zdif = $z1 - $z0; $f3dif = $c*($z1*$z1 - $z0*$z0); $zydif = $zdif*($y1 - $y0); $f2dif = $b*$zdif*($y1*$y1 - $y0*$y0); $f3dif2 = $f3dif*($y1 - $y0);  $xc = $zdif*$a*2; $yc = $zdif*$b*2; $yc2 = $zdif*$b; $zc = ( $f3dif == 1 ) ? '' : $f3dif; $xc2 = $zdif*$a*2*($y1 - $y0);  $xc3 = $zdif*$a*($y1 - $y0);  if ( $x0 != 0 ) {     $v0 = 'y'; $v1 = 'z';     @var = ( 'x', 'x', 'y', 'z' );     @val = ( $x1, $x0, $y1, $z1 );     @int = ( $a*$x1*$x1, $a*$x0*$x0, $b*$y1*$y1, $c*$z1*$z1 ); } elsif ( $y0 != 0 ) {     $v0 = 'x'; $v1 = 'z';     @var = ( 'x', 'y', 'y', 'z' );     @val = ( $x1, $y1, $y0, $z1 );     @int = ( $a*$x1*$x1, $b*$y1*$y1, $b*$y0*$y0, $c*$z1*$z1 );     @lim = ( $y0, $y1, $z0, $z1, 	     $x0, $x1, $z0, $z1, 	     $x0, $x1, $z0, $z1, 	     $x0, $x1, $y0, $y1 );     @dv  = ( 'z', 'y', 'z', 'x', 'z', 'x', 'y', 'x' );     @fl  = ( $x1flux, $y1flux, $y0flux, $z1flux ); } else {     $v0 = 'x'; $v1 = 'y';     @var = ( 'x', 'y', 'z', 'z' );     @val = ( $x1, $y1, $z1, $z0 );     @int = ( $a*$x1*$x1, $b*$y1*$y1, $c*$z1*$z1, $c*$z0*$z0 );     @lim = ( $y0, $y1, $z0, $z1, 	     $x0, $x1, $z0, $z1, 	     $x0, $x1, $y0, $y1, 	     $x0, $x1, $y0, $y1 );     @dv  = ( 'z', 'y', 'z', 'x', 'y', 'x', 'y', 'x' );     @fl  = ( $x1flux, $y1flux, $z1flux, $z0flux ); }  Context()->texStrings; SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR SOLUTION $PAR  Using the Divergence Theorem: \[\mbox{div}\,{\vec{F}} = $f1d + $f2d + $f3d.\] So, if \(W\) is the interior of the box, we have \[ \int_{S}\vec{F} \cdot d\vec{A} = \int_{W}($f1d + $f2d + $f3d)dV = \int_{$x0}^{$x1}\int_{$y0}^{$y1}\int_{$z0}^{$z1}($f1d + $f2d + $f3d)dz\,dy\,dx. \] Integrating through each of the integrals in turn, we have \[ \int_{S}\vec{F} \cdot d\vec{A} = \int_{$x0}^{$x1}\int_{$y0}^{$y1} $f1d\,z + $f2d\,z + $f3\bigg|_{z=$z0}^{z=$z1}\, dy\,dx \] \[ = \int_{$x0}^{$x1}\int_{$y0}^{$y1} $xc x + $yc y + $f3dif\,dy\,dx \] \[ = \int_{$x0}^{$x1} $xc x y + $yc2 y^2 + $zc y\bigg|_{y=$y0}^{y=$y1}\,dx \] \[ = \int_{$x0}^{$x1} $xc2 x + $f2dif + $f3dif2\, dx \] \[ = $xc3 x^2 + $f2dif x + $f3dif2 x\bigg|_{x=$x0}^{x=$x1} \] \[ = $flux. \]  $PAR Finding flux directly, note that on the faces \(x=$x1\) and \(x=$x0\) the normal vectors to the surfaces are \(\vec i\) and \(-\vec i\) respectively, so that \(\vec F\cdot d\vec A = \pm $f1\,dy\,dz\) (where \(x\) is evaluated at $x1 or $x0), and similarly on \(y = $y1\) and \(y = $y0\), and \(z = $z1\) and \(z = $z0\), \(\vec F\cdot d\vec A = \pm $f2\,dx\,dz\) and \(\vec F\cdot d\vec A = \pm $f3\,dx\,dy\), respectively.  Thus on \($v0 = 0\) and \($v1 = 0\) the flux is zero.  On the remaining faces, we have  (1) On \($var[0] = $val[0]\), \(\vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_{$lim[0]}^{$lim[1]}\int_{$lim[2]}^{$lim[3]}\,$int[0]\,d$dv[0]\,d$dv[1] = $fl[0]\);  (2) On \($var[1] = $val[1]\), \(\vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_{$lim[4]}^{$lim[5]}\int_{$lim[6]}^{$lim[7]}\,$int[1]\,d$dv[2]\,d$dv[3] = $fl[1]\);  (3) On \($var[2] = $val[2]\), \(\vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_{$lim[8]}^{$lim[9]}\int_{$lim[10]}^{$lim[11]}\,$int[2]\,d$dv[4]\,d$dv[5] = $fl[2]\); and

EOT ANS(fun_cmp("x+2", limits=>[[2,6]], vars=>["x"]));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  and \(f(f(x))  =( \)  \{ ans_rule(15) \} \()/( \) EOT ANS(fun_cmp("x+1", limits=>[[2,6]], vars=>["x"])); TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \{ ans_rule(15) \} \( ) \) EOT ANS(fun_cmp("x+2", limits=>[[2,6]], vars=>["x"]));  TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  Hint:  Take the definition of \(f\) and replace \(x\) with what ever you are evaluating \(f\) at. EOT   SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD \[ \begin{array}{rcl} \displaystyle  f(x+1) &=& \displaystyle \frac{1}{(x+1)+1} = \displaystyle \frac{1}{x+2}\\ \\ f(f(x)) &=& \displaystyle \frac{1}{1+f(x)} =\displaystyle  \frac{1}{1+\displaystyle \frac{1}{x+1}} =  \displaystyle  \frac{1}{\displaystyle \frac{x+2}{x+1}} = \frac{x+1}{x+2}  \\ \end{array}  \]

question_text: Evaluate the indefinite integral.    \( \displaystyle\int \sin($ax)\cos($b x)\ dx= \) \{ans_rule( 30) \} \(+C\) EOT  ANS(fun_cmp($funct, mode=>"antider"));  $soln_amb = $a-$b; $soln_apb = $a+$b; $soln_2amb = 2*$soln_amb; $soln_2apb = 2*$soln_apb;  &SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $SOL    We use the the identity  \(\sin A\cos B=\frac 1 2 \left[\sin(A-B)+\sin(A+B)\right]\):  \[ \begin{aligned} \int \sin($ax)\cos($b x)dx &=	\int \frac 1 2 \left(\sin($a x-$b x)+\sin($a x+$b x)\right) dx	\\\\ &=	\frac 1 2 \int \sin($soln_amb x)dx 		+ \frac 1 2 \int \sin($soln_apb x)dx	\\\\ &=	\frac{\cos($soln_amb x)}{$soln_2amb} 		+ \frac{\cos($soln_apb x)}{$soln_2apb} +C \end{aligned} \]

An $BITALIC isosceles triangle$EITALIC is one where two sides have the same length and the third side has a possibly different length. Suppose you have an isosceles triangle where two sides have length  \(a\) and the base has length \(b\).  Then the height of that triangle is \(h=\)  \{ ans_rule(24) \}. EOT  ANS(fun_cmp("sqrt(a**2-b**2/4)", limits=>[[4,5],[1,2]], vars=>["a","b"]));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  The area of your triangle is \(A=\)  \{ ans_rule(24) \}. EOT  ANS(fun_cmp("b/2*sqrt(a**2-b**2/4)", limits=>[[4,5],[1,2]], vars=>["a","b"]));         TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Hint:$EBOLD  Draw the right triangle and its height.  Apply the Pythagorean Theorem. Use \(sqrt(...)\) to enter the square root of something.  The area of a triangle is one half times base times height. EOT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD Denote the height by \(h\).  It forms a right triangle where the other short side has length \(a\) and   the hypotenuse has length \(b\).  Thus \(h\) satisfies the equation \[h^2+\frac{b^2}{4} = a^2\] which has the solution \[h=\sqrt{a^2-\frac{b^2}{4}}.\] Substituting in the area formula for the triangle we obtain \[A=\frac{b}{2}h = \frac{b}{2}\sqrt{a^2-\frac{b^2}{4}}.\]

Give the growth factor \(b\), the starting value \(a\), the growth rate \(r\), and the value of \(k\) when \(Q\) is written in the form \(Q = ae^{kt}\). If there is exponential is decay, then your growth rate should negative. For help entering logarithms, see \{ AnswerFormatHelp("logarithms") \}   \( Q = $a e^{$k t} \) has:  $PAR \( b = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \} \{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}  \( a = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \} \{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}  \( r = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \} \{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}  \( k = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \} \{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}  END_TEXT Context()->normalStrings;  ANS( Compute("e^($k)")->cmp() ); ANS( Real("$a")->cmp() ); ANS( Compute("e^{$k}-1")->cmp() ); ANS( Real("$k")->cmp() );  #ANS(num_cmp($a) ); #ANS(num_cmp($b,tol=>0.0006) );  $br = round(10000*$b)/10000; $rr = round(10000*$r)/10000;  Context()->texStrings; SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR $BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD $PAR The continuous percent growth rate is the value of \(k\) in the equation \( Q=ae^{kt} \), which is $k.  To convert to the form \( Q=ab^t \), we first say that the right sides of the two equations equal each other (since each equals \(Q\)), and then we solve for \(a\) and \(b\).  Thus, we have \( ab^{t}= $a e^{$k t} \). At \(t = 0\), we can solve for \(a\): \[\begin{aligned} a\, b^0 &= $a e^{$k\cdot 0} = $a,\quad\mbox{or}\\ a\cdot 1 = $a\cdot 1, \end{aligned} \] so \( a = $a\).  Thus, we have \( $a b^{t} = $a e^{$k t} \), and we solve for \( b \): \[\begin{aligned} $a b^t &= $a e^{$k t} \\ b^{t} &= e^{$k t} \\ b^t &= \left( e^{$k} \right)^t \\ b &= e^{$k}. \end{aligned}\]  Thus we have \( b = e^{$k} \) (about $br), \( a = $a \), \( r = b - 1 = e^{$k} - 1 \) (about $rr), and \( k = $k \).

This problem is an example of "simple Hindu Algebra", quoted on page 528 of "The Story of Civilization", v.1., by Will Durant, Simon and Schuster, 1935.  The problems are approximately 1,800 years old.  (Mental pursuits by women were discouraged at that time. You ponder the significance of fictitiously directing the questions at women.  Durant does not comment on this issue.)     Out of a swarm of bees one fifth part settled on a Kadamba blossom; one third on a Silihindra flower; three times the difference of those numbers flew to the bloom of a Kutaja.  One bee, which remained, hovered about in the air.  Tell me, charming woman, the number of bees  \{ ans_rule(10) \}. EOT ANS(num_cmp(15));   TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  Hint: Call the number of bees \(x\) and convert the story into an equation. EOT   SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD Let \(x\) be the number of bees. Then the story tells us that \[x-\frac{x}{5} -\frac{x}{3} - 3\left(\frac{x}{3}-\frac{x}{5}\right) = 1.\] Applying the Distributive Law and combining the fractions gives \[\left(1-\frac{1}{5} -\frac{1}{3} -3 \left(\frac{1}{3}-\frac{1}{5}\right)\right)x = \frac{15-3-5-3(5-3)}{15}x = \frac{1}{15} x = 1.\] Thus there are 15 bees.  Note that when the problem refers to "the difference of these two numbers" we need to subtract one fifth from one third, since otherwise the number of bees on the bloom of a Kutaja would be negative.

The brightness \(B\) of a star, called its "apparent magnitude" \(m\), is expressed on a logarithmic scale: \[B = a^{-m} B_0\] where \[a=\root 5 \of 100 \approx 2.511886432\] and \(B_0\) is a reference brightness. Notice the minus sign in the exponent, the smaller \(m\) the brighter is the object!  For example, the star Vega has an apparent magnitude close to zero.  The dimmest stars visible to the naked eye have an apparent magnitude close to six.  The brightest star in the sky, Sirius, has an apparent magnitude of \(-1.4\) and Venus may be as bright as \(-4.4\) (depending on its distance and phase).    The full moon has an apparent magnitude of \(-12.6\).  It is   \{ ans_rule(10) \} times as bright as Sirius.  EOT  ANS(num_cmp($a**(12.6-1.4), mode=>"strict"));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));      The sun is  449,000 times as bright as the full moon, thus its apparent magnitude is  \{ ans_rule(10) \}.

$BCENTER Suppose you are given a right triangle with hypotenuse of length \(r\) and legs of length \(x-$d\) and \(x+$d\).       \{ image( insertGraph($gr),  width=>250,height=>350,tex_size=>500 ) \} $PAR Determine formulas (based upon \(r\)) for the lengths of the two legs.   $PAR Shorter leg = \{ans_rule(20)\}  Longer leg  = \{ans_rule(20)\} $ECENTER END_TEXT  Context("Numeric");  ANS($a->cmp(limits => [9,10])); ANS($b->cmp(limits => [9,10]));  BEGIN_HINT $PAR Apply the Pythagorean Theorem with \(a = (x-$d)\), \(b = (x+$d)\) and \(c = r\). Since \(r\) is not given then your final answer will be a formula with r still in it.   END_HINT  Context()->texStrings;  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $PAR  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD   By using the Pythagorean Theorem \[ (x-$d)^2 + (x+$d)^2 = r^2\] \[ x^2 - 2 ($d) x + $d^2 + x^2 + 2 ($d) x + $d^2 = r^2\] \[ 2x^2 + 2($d^2) = r^2 \] \[ x^2 = (r^2-2($d^2))/2\] and taking square roots gives \[ x = \sqrt{(r^2-2($d^2))/2}\]  Therefore, \(a = \sqrt{\frac{r^2-2($d^2)}{2}} - $d = $a\) and  \(b = \sqrt{\frac{r^2-2($d^2)}{2}} + $d = $b\)

Consider the formula for one of the solutions of a quadratic equation:  \[x= \frac{-b+\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\]  For each of the WeBWorK phrases below enter a $BITALIC T$EITALIC (true) if the phrase describes \(x\), correctly, and a $BITALIC F$EITALIC (false) otherwise.    You need to get all answers correct before obtaining credit.	      \{ ans_rule(4) \}  \( -b+sqrt(b**2-4*a*c)/2a\)    EOT  ANS(str_cmp("F"));   TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));     \{ ans_rule(4) \}  \( (-b+sqrt(b**2-4*a*c))/2a\)   EOT ANS(str_cmp("F"));   TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));     \{ ans_rule(4) \}  \( \frac{-b+ \sqrt{b^2-4ac}}/{2a}\)   EOT ANS(str_cmp("T"));   SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD    $BBOLD -b+sqrt(b**2-4*a*c)/2a $EBOLD means \[-b +\frac{\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2} \times a\] which is quite different.  The reason for the confusion is that division and multiplication have the same precedence and proceed from left to right unless otherwise indicated with parentheses.  Thus we divide by 2, and then multiply the result with a.  Also the scope of the division is only the square root since division comes before the addition to \(b\).   $BBOLD (-b+sqrt(b**2-4*a*c))/2a$EBOLD is a little better in that \(-b\) is included in the numerator, but the final \(a\) is still in the numerator rather than the denominator.  The expression means: \[\frac{-b +\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2} \times a\].   The last expression, $BBOLD (-b+sqrt(b**2-4*a*c))/(2a)$EBOLD is the correct answer for this problem.

$BBOLD Note:$EBOLD You can get full credit for this problem by just answering the last question correctly. The initial questions are meant as hints towards the final answer and also allow you the opportunity to get partial credit. This is a problem with multiple parts.  When you complete a part and are told that  your answers are correct t then click to go on to the next part and resubmit your answer. When you do this ignore the statement that  there are unanswered questions and just answer the new questions. $PAR When you first saw exponents they were positive integers.   They counted the number of copies of the base that were to be multiplied together.  For example, \(5^3 = 5\cdot 5\cdot 5=125\).   You can refresh your memory by calculating a few examples:    $PAR \(7^2=\)\{ans_rule(2)\} $PAR \(3^5=\)\{ans_rule(2)\} $PAR If someone asked you to compute \(3^0\) or \(9^{\frac{1}{2}}\) your  reaction would be   that the question is ridiculous  because you can't multiply no threes together  nor can you multiply a half of a nine together,  and, based on what you have been taught so far  your reaction would be totally reasonable.    But mathematicians have found things like \(3^0\) and \(9^{\frac{1}{2}}\) to be useful   and they used a very important technique to find a reasonable way to deal with them.    Since this method will arise in several topics you will study in middle and high school,  we will explain it in detail. $PAR The trick is to find an explanation other than   " the number of copies of the base to multiply together" for the exponent  in such a way that it will give the same result on the things we  already know   and enable us to use exponents that are not positive integers. $PAR Suppose we let the positive number \(b\) be the base and make the  following definition:  Rule 1: \(b^1=b\)    Rule 2: \(b^{n+1}=b^n\cdot b\) $PAR This definition must look strange to you so let us use it to find \(5^3\).    The base is \(5\) so we can use Rule 1 to say that \(5^1=5\).   Now that we know what \(5^1\) is we can use Rule 2 to say that \(5^2=5^{1+1}=5^1\cdot 5 =5\cdot 5=25\).    Next we can use Rule 2 to say \(5^3=5^{2+1}=5^2\cdot 5 =25\cdot 5=125\).    This is much uglier than just saying that \(5^3=5\cdot 5\cdot 5\). But now we can do some neat tricks with it. $PAR Notice that in Rule 2 we did not say that n had to be a positive integer.   So we will use the definition to find out what \(5^0\) has to be.   But you can do some of the work. $PAR  We know from rule 1 that \(5^1=5\).   From Rule 2 we can say That \(5^{0+1}=5^{0}\cdot 5\).   Now if \(5^0\) is a number which multiplied by 5 gives us \(5^{0+1}\)   then we know that  \(5^0\) = \{ans_rule(1)\}   END_TEXT   Context()->normalStrings;  ############################################################## # # Answers # # Context("LimitedNumeric");   ANS(Real($ans1)->cmp,Real($ans2)->cmp, Real(1)-> cmp );   } # End of Part 1  ############################################## # # Part 2 #   if ($part == 2) {   BEGIN_TEXT Part 2: Recall that we are looking at the consequences  the following two rules for exponents. $PAR Rule 1: \(b^1=b\)    Rule 2: \(b^{n+1}=b^n\cdot b\) $PAR Now you have seen how we showed that \(5^0=1\). You  can use the same technique that \(7^0=1\).    Now you are probably tempted to believe that if \(n\) is any number then \(n^0=1\).  But that is false and let us see why.  Let's try to see what \(0^0\)  must be. $PAR Certainly we can use Rule 1 to say that \(0^1=0\). Now we use Rule 2 to say \(0^{0+1}=0^0\cdot 0\).    This tells us that \(0=0^0\cdot 0\).  But, unfortunately this tells us nothing since if we multiply any  number by 0 we get 0.   So these rules do not tell us what \(0^0\) should be. $PAR Well, you may say, we should use common sense to figure out what  \(0^0\) has to be. $PAR You might say $PAR  Claim 1:  If for any positive number n, \(n^0=1\) then \(0^0\)  should be 1. $PAR Now let's see what is wrong with this reasoning.  First, we know that \(0^1=0\).$ Notice that \(0^2\) (the result of multiplying two zeros together) is also \(0\). In fact, \(0^n=0\) for any positive integer \(n\).  So you could say $PAR  Claim 2:  If for any positive number n, \(0^n=0\) then \(0^0\) should be 0.  The two claims are equally strong, and it turns out that there is no reasonable way to define \(0^0\). $PAR Now we will go a few steps further.  Using Rule 2 and the fact that you know that \(5^0=1\) find each of the following. $PAR \(5^{-1}=\) \{ans_rule(3)\}. $PAR \(5^{-2}=\)\{ans_rule(5)\}.  END_TEXT  ############################################################## # # Answers # # Context("Fraction");  ANS(Compute("1/5")->cmp); ANS(Compute("1/25")->cmp); Context("Numeric"); } # End of Part 2  ############################################## # # Part 3 #   if ($part == 3) {  Context()->texStrings; BEGIN_TEXT Part 3:   Now we will try to figure out how to extend to fractional powers.  At this point you will just have to believe that it will be useful. $PAR If you just look at positive integer powers you can see that \(5^4\cdot 5^3=5^7\)  This comes from the fact that if you multiply four fives together and then multiply this by the product of three fives you end up by multiplying seven fives together.  Using the same reasoning you can see that positive integer powers satisfy: $PAR Rule 3: \(b^m\cdot b^n=b^{m+n}\). $PAR If you think a bit about what you have done with negative integer powers you can see that this rule works for them too.   So we will add Rule 3  to our rules for exponents (so that it applies to all exponents).$PAR This may worry you a bit.  How can we just make up such rules?  Well, since we have no way to interpret powers that are not positive integers, in terms of multiplying copies of the base together  and since the rule works when in the case of positive integers, we are making an extension and can only judge whether it is useful.   $PAR Now we will look at what happens when we extend this rule to the situation in which \(m \)and \(n \) are permitted to be fractions.  We will first look at an example.  Use Rule 3 to answer the next question. $PAR  \(5^{\frac{1}{2}} \cdot 5^{\frac{1}{2]}=\) \{ans_rule(2)\} END_TEXT ############################################################## # # Answers  Context("Numeric"); ANS(Real (5)-> cmp); } #end of part 3 ############################################## # # Part 4 #   if ($part == 4) {    Context()->texStrings; $ans10="sqrt(5)"; BEGIN_TEXT Part 4: $PAR Now we have  the following three rules for exponents. $PAR Rule 1: \(b^1=b\)    Rule 2: \(b^{n+1}=b^n\cdot b\)  Rule 3: \(b^m\cdot b^n=b^{m+n}\). $PAR $PAR Now since \(5^{\frac{1}{2}}\cdot 5^{\frac{1}{2}}=5\) we know that     \(5^{\frac{1}{2}}\) is a number that, when multiplied by itself gives the product 5.   Actually there are two numbers that satisfy that condition, namely \(\sqrt{5}\) and \(-\sqrt{5}\)   but we add the rule that we always choose the positive root when faced with such a choice.   You might want to check that for integer values of n this rule is satisfied. $PAR Rule 4: If \(b\) is positive then \(b^n\) is positive for any n. $PAR Now we know that  \(5^{\frac{1}{2}}= \sqrt{5}\).    To put in \(\sqrt{5}\) as an answer you must type it as sqrt(5).  Check that it works for you. $PAR  \(5^{\frac{1}{2}}=\) \{ans_rule(4)\} END_TEXT ############################################################## # # Answers  ANS(str_cmp($ans10)); } #end of part 4 ############################################## # # Part 5 #   if ($part == 5) {  Context()->texStrings; BEGIN_TEXT Part 5:  $PAR Of course, you must always simplify your answer as much as possible, for example  \(4^{\frac{1}{2}}=\) \{ans_rule(2)\} END_TEXT ############################################################## # # Answers  ANS(Real (2)-> cmp); } #end of part 5  ############################################## # # Part 6 #   if ($part == 6) {    Context()->texStrings; $ans14="root[6](7)"; BEGIN_TEXT Part 6: $PAR To deal with more complicated fractional exponents we must start by  listing a few consequences of Rule 3. $PAR  Rule 3a:  \(b^{nk}=(b^n)^k\) $PAR An example of this rule is that \(5^{3\cdot 2}=(5^3)^2\).  Notice that all the example says is that if we multiply six fives together that is the same thing as multiplying the product of three fives by itself.  You can check that Rule 3a is certainly true for integer exponents, for example $PAR \(2^{3\cdot 3}=( a^b)^c \) where a, b, and c are the integers: $PAR  a= \{ans_rule(1)\}  b= \{ans_rule(1)\}  c= \{ans_rule(1)\}  $PAR Earlier we used the fact that  \(5^{\frac{1}{2}}\cdot 5^{\frac{1}{2}}=5\).  in order to show that \(5^{\frac{1}{2}}=\sqrt{5}\).     Another way of saying the same thing is that \((5^{\frac{1}{2}})^2=5\) and this means that  \(5^{\frac{1}{2}\times 2}=5\) $PAR Using this second approach we can see that  \(5^{\frac{1}{3}\times 3}=5\). This tells us that \(5^{\frac{1}{3}}\) is a number whose third power is 5. The mathematical notation for this is \(\root 3 \of 5\)  and it is called the cube root of 5 or the third root of 5.  It would be very difficult for you to use this notation to answer WeBWorK questions. $PAR  We will invent a special notation for answering WeBWorK questions.  If n > 2 then we will use root[n](k) for \(\root n \of k\).  and so \(5^{\frac{1}{3}}\)=root[3](5).     The sixth root of 7 is the positive number whose sixth power is 7. It is written \{ans_rule(8)\}     END_TEXT ############################################################## # # Answers Context("LeadingZero"); ANS(Real(2)->cmp); ANS(Real(3)->cmp); ANS(Real(3)->cmp);  ANS(str_cmp($ans14)); } #end of part 6 ############################################## # # Part 7 #   if ($part == 7) {  Context()->texStrings;  $ans16=  "root[4](27)";  BEGIN_TEXT Part 7: Now, we will put all of our information together to deal with some  problems that even many college students have great trouble with. $PAR We will first interpret \(4^{\frac {3}{2}}\).  \(4^{\frac {3}{2}}=4^{\frac {1}{2}\cdot 3}= \(4^{\frac {1}{2}}^3\)  But we know that \(4^{\frac {1}{2}}=2\).  So  \(4^{\frac {3}{2}}=2^3=8\).  $PAR Now, we always want our expressions as simple as possible.   \(9^\frac{1}{2}\) could be written root[2](9)  or it could be written \(\sqrt(9)\)  or it could be written 3.    But since 3 is so much easier to understand, we will insist that if an answer is really an integer  we will call that integer the "best" form of the answer.   If not and if the answer is the square root of an integer then we will call that the best form.   If it is neither an integer nor the square root of an integer, we will use the root[a](n) notation where n is an integer. $PAR Find the best form for each of the following. $PAR  $PAR    \(8^{\frac{2}{3}}= \) \{ans_rule(10)\} $PAR  \(3^{\frac{3}{4}}= \) \{ans_rule(10)\} $PAR \(32^{\frac{2}{5}}= \) \{ans_rule(10)\} $PAR  \(16^{\frac{3}{2}}= \) \{ans_rule(10)\}

latex_expressions: ['\\( \\displaystyle \\int_{$a}^{$d} f(x) dx =$a1, \\int_{$a}^{$b} f(x) dx=$a2,  \\int_{$c}^{$d} f(x)dx =$a3 \\)', '\\( \\displaystyle \\int_{$b}^{$c} f(x)dx= \\)', '\\( \\displaystyle \\int_{$b}^{$c} ($a1 f(x)- $a2)dx= \\)', '\\( \\displaystyle \t\\int_{$b}^{$c} ($a1 f(x) - $a2) dx \t\t=\t\\int_{$b}^{$c} $a1 f(x) dx - \\int_{$b}^{$c} $a2 dx\t\\)', '\\( \\displaystyle \t=\t$a1 \\int_{$b}^{$c} f(x) dx - \\int_{$b}^{$c} $a2 dx\t\\)', '\\( \\displaystyle \t=\t$a1 \\int_{$b}^{$c} f(x) dx - $a2($c - $b)\t\t\\)', '\\( \\displaystyle \t=\t$a1($soln_fin1) - $a2($c - $b)\t\t\t\t\\)', '\\( \\displaystyle \t=\t$soln_tmp1 - $soln_tmp2 = $soln_fin2 \\)', '\\[  \\int_{a}^{b} f(x) dx + \\int_{b}^{c} f(x) dx = \\int_{a}^{c} f(x) dx  \\]', '\\[  \\int_{b}^{c} f(x) dx = \\int_{a}^{c} f(x) dx - \\int_{a}^{b} f(x) dx  \\]', '\\[ \t\\int_{$b}^{$d} f(x) dx \t\t= \\int_{$a}^{$d} f(x) dx - \\int_{$a}^{$b} f(x) dx \t\t= $a1 - $a2 = $soln_a1a2 \t\\]', '\\[\t\\int_{a}^{b} f(x) dx = \\int_{a}^{c} f(x) dx - \\int_{b}^{c} f(x) dx\t\\]', '\\[ \t\\int_{$b}^{$c} f(x) dx \t\t= \\int_{$b}^{$d} f(x) dx - \\int_{$c}^{$d} f(x) dx \t\t= $soln_a1a2 - $a3 = $soln_fin1 \t\\]']
question_text: Let \( \displaystyle \int_{$a}^{$d} f(x) dx =$a1, \int_{$a}^{$b} f(x) dx=$a2,  \int_{$c}^{$d} f(x)dx =$a3 \).   Find \( \displaystyle \int_{$b}^{$c} f(x)dx= \) \{ans_rule( 10)\}  and \( \displaystyle \int_{$b}^{$c} ($a1 f(x)- $a2)dx= \) \{ans_rule( 10)\} EOT  $ans1=$a1-$a2-$a3; $ans2=$a1*$ans1-$a2*$b1;  ANS(num_cmp($ans1), num_cmp($ans2));  $soln_a1a2 = $a1-$a2; $soln_fin1 = $soln_a1a2-$a3; $soln_tmp1 = $a1*$soln_fin1; $soln_tmp2 = $a2*($c-$b); $soln_fin2 = $soln_tmp1-$soln_tmp2;  &SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $SOL    First recall the following fact from p.386 of your textbook:     \[  \int_{a}^{b} f(x) dx + \int_{b}^{c} f(x) dx = \int_{a}^{c} f(x) dx  \] and therefore we can rearrange it to look like this:     \[  \int_{b}^{c} f(x) dx = \int_{a}^{c} f(x) dx - \int_{a}^{b} f(x) dx  \]   Applying that in this specific context, we find: 	\[ 	\int_{$b}^{$d} f(x) dx 		= \int_{$a}^{$d} f(x) dx - \int_{$a}^{$b} f(x) dx 		= $a1 - $a2 = $soln_a1a2 	\] This is not our final answer, however; it is only an intermediate step.    We can also rearrange the original formula above to achieve the following: 	\[	\int_{a}^{b} f(x) dx = \int_{a}^{c} f(x) dx - \int_{b}^{c} f(x) dx	\] We use it as we proceed: 	\[ 	\int_{$b}^{$c} f(x) dx 		= \int_{$b}^{$d} f(x) dx - \int_{$c}^{$d} f(x) dx 		= $soln_a1a2 - $a3 = $soln_fin1 	\] This is the answer to the first question in this problem.        As for the second question, we can use a few properties of the integral introduced on p.385 of your text:  \( \displaystyle 	\int_{$b}^{$c} ($a1 f(x) - $a2) dx 		=	\int_{$b}^{$c} $a1 f(x) dx - \int_{$b}^{$c} $a2 dx	\)  				by Property #4 				(integral of difference is difference of integrals)	  \( \displaystyle 	=	$a1 \int_{$b}^{$c} f(x) dx - \int_{$b}^{$c} $a2 dx	\)  				by Property #3 (can pull constant out of integral)	  \( \displaystyle 	=	$a1 \int_{$b}^{$c} f(x) dx - $a2($c - $b)		\) 	 				by Property #1 (integral of constant formula)		  \( \displaystyle 	=	$a1($soln_fin1) - $a2($c - $b)				\)   				by substituting answer to first part of problem		  \( \displaystyle 	=	$soln_tmp1 - $soln_tmp2 = $soln_fin2 \)

question_text: Compute the indefinite integral \[ \int ($a x^{$b} + $c \sec(x)\tan(x)) dx \]  \{ans_rule(30)\} EOT  $answer="$a/($b+1)*x**($b+1)+$c*sec(x)";  ANS(fun_cmp($answer, mode=>"antider"));  $soln_bp1 = $b + 1;  &SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $SOL    Recall that the derivative with respect to \(x\) of \(\sec(x)\) is \(\sec(x)\tan(x)\).  Thus the problem is solved as follows: \[ \begin{aligned} \int ($a x^{$b} + $c \sec(x)\tan(x)) dx &=	$a \int x^{$b} dx + $c \int \sec(x)\tan(x) dx	\\\\ &=	\frac{$a}{$soln_bp1}x^{$b+1} + $c \sec(x) + C \end{aligned} \]

Determine the number of possible ring homomorphisms for each pair of rings:    (a) \( \{ cyclic( $a ) \} \rightarrow \{ cyclic( $a ) \} \): \{ ans_rule( 10 ) \}    (b) \( \{ cyclic( $m1 ) \} \rightarrow \{ cyclic( $n1 ) \} \): \{ ans_rule( 10 ) \}    (c) \( \{ cyclic( $m2 ) \} \rightarrow \{ cyclic( $n2 ) \} \): \{ ans_rule( 10 ) \}    Note:  Recall that ring homomorphisms take the multiplicative identity to multiplicative identity.  EOT  ANS( $ans[ 0 ]->cmp ); ANS( $ans[ 1 ]->cmp ); ANS( $ans[ 2 ]->cmp );  Context()->texStrings;  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $SOLUTION  If \(f: \{ cyclic( 'm' ) \} \rightarrow \{ cyclic( 'n' ) \} \)  is a ring homomorphism then    \[ \begin{aligned} 	(**) \; f( a 1_{ \{ cyclic( 'm' ) \} } ) &= a f( 1_{ \{ cyclic( 'm' ) \} } ) \\ 	&=  a 1_{ \{ cyclic( 'n' ) \} } \end{aligned} \]  Since every element of \( \{ cyclic( 'm' ) \} \) is of the form \( a 1_{ \{ cyclic( 'm' ) \} } \) for some integer \( a \), the requirement $PAR  \[ (*) \textrm{ a ring homomorphism } f: A \rightarrow B \textrm{ takes } 1_A \textrm{ to } 1_B \]  means that for any integers \( m, n \) there is at most one ring homomorphism from \( \{ cyclic( 'm' ) \} \) to \( \{ cyclic( 'n' ) \} \).  On the other hand, by properties of ring homomorphisms we get $PAR  \[ \begin{aligned} 	0_{ \{ cyclic( 'n' ) \} } &= f( 0_{ \{ cyclic( 'm' ) \} } ) \\ 	&= f( m 1_{ \{ cyclic( 'm' ) \} } ) \\ 	&= m f( 1_{ \{ cyclic( 'm' ) \} } \\ 	&= m 1_{ \{ cyclic( 'n' ) \} } \end{aligned} \]  so in order for \( f \)  to be a ring homomorphism we need \( n \) to divide \( m \). And if \( n \) does divide \( m \), we check that \( (**) \) does satisfy the definition of ring homomorphisms. Actually -- and this is important -- there are two things to check:

EOT ANS(fun_cmp("(x+$a)*(x+$b)", limits=>[[-5,-1]], vars=>["x"]));   TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \(\frac{1}{x+$a} \times \frac{1}{x+$b} =( \)  \{ ans_rule(15) \} \()/( \) EOT ANS(fun_cmp("1", vars=>["x"])); TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \{ ans_rule(15) \} \( ) \). EOT ANS(fun_cmp("(x+$a)*(x+$b)", limits=>[[-5,-1]], vars=>["x"]));   TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \(\frac{1}{x+$a} \div \frac{1}{x+$b} =( \)  \{ ans_rule(15) \} \()/( \) EOT ANS(fun_cmp("x+$b", vars=>["x"])); TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \{ ans_rule(15) \} \( ) \). EOT ANS(fun_cmp("x+$a", limits=>[[-5,-1]], vars=>["x"]));   TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  Hint:  Rational expressions work just like fractions. EOT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD We have \[ \begin{array}{rcl} \frac{1}{x+$a}+\frac{1}{x+$b} &=& \frac{x+$a+x+$b}{(x+$a)(x+$b)} \\ \frac{1}{x+$a}-\frac{1}{x+$b} &=& \frac{x+$a-(x+$b)}{(x+$a)(x+$b)} \\ \frac{1}{x+$a}\times\frac{1}{x+$b} &=& \frac{1}{(x+$a)(x+$b)} \\ \frac{1}{x+$a}\div\frac{1}{x+$b} &=& \frac{x+$b}{x+$a} \\ \end{array} \]  Some of these answers can be further simplified, but WeBWorK will accept them in the given form.

Consider the two points \( ($x1 ,$y1 )\) and \( ($x2 ,$y2 )\). $PAR The distance between them is: \{ans_rule(20) \}  END_TEXT $ans = $len1; ANS(num_cmp($ans));  BEGIN_TEXT The midpoint of the line segment that joins these points is: (\{ans_rule(20)\} , \{ans_rule(20)\}) END_TEXT  ANS(num_cmp($midx));  ANS(num_cmp($midy));  $dsq = ($x1 - $x2)**2 + ($y1 - $y2)**2;  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOF')); $SOL                                Recall that for two points \(P(x_1, y_1)\) and \(Q(x_2,y_2)\), the distance between \(P\) and \(Q\) is  \[ |PQ|=\sqrt{(x_2-x_1)^2+(y_2-y_1)^2} \] and the coordinates of the midpoint of the segment that joins \(P\) and \(Q\) are  \[ x_m = \frac{x_1+x_2}{2}, \ \ \ \ \ y_m = \frac{y_1+y_2}{2} \]  Therefore the distance between \( ($x1 ,$y1 )\) and \( ($x2 ,$y2 )\) is  \[ d=\sqrt{($x2 - $x1)^2+($y2 - $y1)^2} = \sqrt{$dsq} = $len1 \]  and the coordinates of the midpoints are   \[ x_m = \frac{$x1+$x2}{2} = $midx, \ \ \ \ \ y_m = \frac{$y1+$y2}{2} = $midy \]  Note: if you did not know the formulas for the coordinates of the midpoint, you could just draw a  coordinate system, plot the given points, and find the midpoint of the segment joining them. You would see from the picture what are the coordinates of the midpoint.

A light, flashing regularly, consists of cycles, each cycle having a dark phase and a light phase.  The frequency of this light is measured in cycles per second. latex_expressions: ['\\( f(x) = $a x^2 \\arctan(x^{$b}) \\)', '\\( \\displaystyle f(x) = \\sum_{n=0}^\\infty c_n x^n .\\)', '\\( n = \\)', '\\( R \\)', '\\( R = \\)', '\\( \\tan^{-1} \\)', '\\( \\displaystyle $a x^2 \\tan^{-1}(x^{$b}) = $a x^2 \\sum_{n=0}^\\infty (-1)^n \\frac{(x^{$b})^{2n+1}}{2n+1} \\)', '\\($soln_bp2\\)', '\\( x^{$soln_2b} < 1 \\)', '\\( \\left| x \\right| < 1 \\)', '\\[ \\begin{aligned} $a x^2 \\sum_{n=0}^\\infty (-1)^n \\frac{(x^{$b})^{2n+1}}{2n+1} &=\t$a x^2 \\sum_{n=0}^\\infty (-1)^n \\frac{x^{$soln_2b n+$b}}{2n+1}\t\\\\\\\\ &=\t\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty (-1)^n \t\t\\left( \\frac{$a}{2n+1} \\right) x^{$soln_2b n+$soln_bp2}\t\\\\\\\\ &=\t\\frac{$a}{1}x^{$soln_bp2} - \\frac{$a}{3}x^{$soln_e1} \t\t+ \\frac{$a}{5}x^{$soln_e2} - \\cdots \\end{aligned} \\]', '\\[ \\begin{aligned} \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\left| \t\\frac{ (-1)^{n+1} \\left(\\frac{$a}{2(n+1)+1}\\right) \t\t\tx^{$soln_2b(n+1)+$soln_bp2} } \t{ (-1)^n \\left(\\frac{$a}{2n+1}\\right) x^{$soln_2b n+$soln_bp2} } \\right| =\t\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\left| \\left(\\frac{2n+1}{2n+3}\\right)x^{$soln_2b} \\right| =\tx^{$soln_2b} \\end{aligned} \\]']
question_text: The function 	\( f(x) = $a x^2 \arctan(x^{$b}) \) is represented as a power series   	\( \displaystyle f(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty c_n x^n .\)  What is the lowest term with a nonzero coefficient.  	\( n = \)  \{ans_rule(20)\}   Find the radius of convergence \( R \) of the series.   	\( R = \)  \{ans_rule(20)\}  .   END_TEXT  #@ans=(); $ans0 =  $b+2 ; $ans1 =  1 ;  #ANS(num_cmp(relTol=>@ans)); #ANS(ordered_num_cmp_list(@ans) ); ANS(num_cmp($ans0)); ANS(num_cmp($ans1));  $soln_2b = $b*2; $soln_bp2 = $b+2; $soln_e1 = $soln_2b + $soln_bp2; $soln_e2 = 2*$soln_2b + $soln_bp2;  &SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $SOL      Working from the Taylor series for \( \tan^{-1} \), we can deduce that \( \displaystyle $a x^2 \tan^{-1}(x^{$b}) = $a x^2 \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n \frac{(x^{$b})^{2n+1}}{2n+1} \), but this expression is a bit complicated, so let's see if we can simplify it a bit, or get a better idea of what it looks like expanded: \[ \begin{aligned} $a x^2 \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n \frac{(x^{$b})^{2n+1}}{2n+1} &=	$a x^2 \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n \frac{x^{$soln_2b n+$b}}{2n+1}	\\\\ &=	\sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n 		\left( \frac{$a}{2n+1} \right) x^{$soln_2b n+$soln_bp2}	\\\\ &=	\frac{$a}{1}x^{$soln_bp2} - \frac{$a}{3}x^{$soln_e1} 		+ \frac{$a}{5}x^{$soln_e2} - \cdots \end{aligned} \] Thus the lowest term with a nonzero coefficient is term \($soln_bp2\).   The radius of convergence can be found with the ratio test: \[ \begin{aligned} \lim_{n\to\infty} \left| 	\frac{ (-1)^{n+1} \left(\frac{$a}{2(n+1)+1}\right) 			x^{$soln_2b(n+1)+$soln_bp2} } 	{ (-1)^n \left(\frac{$a}{2n+1}\right) x^{$soln_2b n+$soln_bp2} } \right| =	\lim_{n\to\infty} \left| \left(\frac{2n+1}{2n+3}\right)x^{$soln_2b} \right| =	x^{$soln_2b} \end{aligned} \] Since \( x^{$soln_2b} < 1 \) exactly when \( \left| x \right| < 1 \), the radius of convergence is 1.

I got the following data from \{htmlLink("http://hyperphysics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/solar/sun.html","this web page:")\} The diameter of the Sun is 1.392 million kilometers. The mean distance of the Sun from the Earth (measured from center to center) is 149 million kilometers.  The surface gravity on the Sun is 274 meters per second squared.  Using those numbers, the escape velocity on the surface of the Sun is \{ans_rule(10)\} kilometers per second.  $PAR For the next part, let's first solve a general problem.  Suppose you have a planet or star of radius \(R\) and surface gravity \(G\). Then the escape velocity on the surface of that object is \{ans_rule(10)\}. (We answered that question in class.).  Now suppose you are already at a distance \(S>R\) from the center of that object.  Then the escape velocity is only \{ans_rule(20)\}.   $PAR Let's apply this to our actual world.  Suppose you are launching a space craft from a point in Earth's orbit.  Ignoring earth's gravity the minimum speed required to cause your craft to leave the solar system is \{ans_rule(10)\} kilometers per second.   EOT $R = 1.392E6/2; $G = 0.274; $S = 149E6; $E = sqrt(2*$G*$R*$R/$S);   ANS(num_cmp(sqrt(2*$G*$R))); ANS(fun_cmp("sqrt(2*G*R)", limits=>[[1,2],[1,2]], vars=>["G","R"])); ANS(fun_cmp("sqrt(2*G*R*R/S)", limits=>[[1,2],[1,2],[1,2]], vars=>["G","R","S"])); ANS(num_cmp(sqrt(2*$G*$R*$R/$S)));   SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));   $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD  We saw in class that the escape velocity on the surface of an object of radius \(R\) and surface gravity \(G\) is \(\sqrt{2GR}\). For the Sun this works out to about 618 km/sec.  To get the escape velocity at a distance \(S\) we modify the analysis discussed in class. The work required to lift an object of mass \(m\) from a distance \(S\) to infinity is \[w= \int_S^\infty mG (\frac{R}{s})^2 $d s = mg\frac{R^2}{S}.\] Equating this with the kinetic energy at launch with a speed \(v_0\) and solving for \(v_o\) gives  \[ mG\frac{R^2}{S} = \frac{1}{2} m v_0^2 \qquad \Longrightarrow \qquad v_0 = \sqrt{\frac{2GR^2}{S}}.\]    On Earth this works out to about 42 kilometers per second squared.  So leaving the solar system from where we are is quite a bit harder harder than just leaving earth.

Recall that a reduced fraction is a fraction \( a/b \) where \( \gcd( a, b ) = 1 \). It is a fact that    \[ \mathbb{Z}_{($p)} := $LB \textrm{ all reduced fractions whose denominators are powers of } $p $RB \] \[ \textrm{ (including the zero-th power) } \]   is a subring of \( \mathbb{Q} \), the ring of rational numbers.    For this problem we require that ring homomorphisms take the multiplicative identity to the multiplicative identity.    (a) Determine the number of ring homomorphisms \( \mathbb{Z}_{($p)} \rightarrow \{ cyclic( $p ) \}. \)   \{ ans_rule( 10 ) \}    (b) Determine the number of ring homomorphisms \( \{ cyclic( $p ) \} \rightarrow \mathbb{Z}_{($p)}. \)   \{ ans_rule( 10 ) \}  EOT  ANS( $ans[ 0 ]->cmp ); ANS( $ans[ 1 ]->cmp );   SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $SOLUTION  Note that \(1/$p\) is a non-zero element in the ring \(    \mathbb{Z}_{($p)} \), and \(  1_{\mathbb{Z}_{($p)}} = (1/$p)\times $p  \).  So if \(   f:   \mathbb{Z}_{($p)} \rightarrow \{ cyclic( $p ) \} \) is a ring homomorphism that takes the multiplicative identity to the  multiplicative identity, then  \( \) \( \) \( \) \(   1_{\{ cyclic( $p ) \}}  =  f(1/$p) f($p)  \).  But  since \(f\) is a ring homomorphism,  \( \) \( \) \( \) \(   f($p)  = $p f(1_{\mathbb{Z}_{($p)}}) = $p \times 1_{\{ cyclic( $p ) \}}           = 0_{ \{ cyclic( $p ) \}}. \)  Combine these two and we arrive at a contradition, so \(f\) does not exist.

question_text: The trough in the figure below has width \(w = $wid\) ft, length  \(L = $len \) ft and height \(h = $hei\) ft. $PAR $BCENTER \{ image( 'q19fig.gif', 'tex_size'=>500 ) \}  ${BITALIC}(Click on the graph for a larger version.)$EITALIC $ECENTER $PAR If the trough is full of water, find the force of the water on a triangular end.  (Use the density of water \(= 62.4\hbox{ lb/ft}^3\).)  Force = \{ ans_rule(35) \}  (include \{ helpLink("units") \})  $PAR Find the work to pump all of the water over the top of the trough.   Work = \{ ans_rule(35) \}  (include \{ helpLink("units") \})  END_TEXT Context()->normalStrings;  ANS( NumberWithUnits( "$wid*62.4*$hei*$hei/6", 'lb' )->cmp() ); ANS( NumberWithUnits( "$len*62.4*$wid*$hei*$hei/6", 'ft*lb' )->cmp() );  $num = $wid; $den = $hei; for ( my $i=$wid; $i>0; $i-- ) {     if ( $num/$i == int($num/$i) && $den/$i == int($den/$i) ) { 	$num = $num/$i;  $den = $den/$i;     } } $woh = "{$num\over $den}"; $hei2 = ( $hei/2 == int($hei/2) ) ? $hei/2 : "{$hei\over 2}"; $frc = $wid*62.4*($hei*$hei/6); $c = round(1000*$wid*$len/$hei)/1000; $c2 = round(1000*$c*62.4)/1000; $wk = round(1000*$len*62.4*$wid*$hei*$hei/6)/1000;  Context()->texStrings; SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR SOLUTION $PAR  We divide the triangular end into horizontal strips of thickness \(\Delta h\). The length of a strip, \(s\), depends on its height \(h\) from the bottom.  We can use similar triangles to find that  \( {s \over h} = {$wid \over $hei}\), so \(s = $woh h\). $PAR Since each strip is approximately a rectangle, at height \(h\), \[ \hbox{Area of strip }\approx $woh h\Delta h\hbox{ ft}^2. \] Since the depth at height \(h\) is \($hei - h\), writing \(\delta\) for the density of water, we have: \[ \hbox{Force on one strip} = \delta \cdot \hbox{Depth} \cdot \hbox{Area}   \approx \delta ($hei - h) \left($woh h \Delta h\right)\hbox{ lb.} \] To find the total force, \(F\), we integrate the force on a strip from \(h = 0\) to \(h = $hei\), using \(\delta=62.4 \hbox{ lb/ft}^3\): \[ F = \int_0^{$hei} \delta ($hei - h)$woh h dh =    $woh \delta \int_0^{$hei} ($hei h - h^2) dh \]  \[ =    ($woh)(62.4) \left( $hei2 h^2 - {h^3 \over 3}\right)\bigg|_0^{$hei} =    $frc \hbox{ lbs.} \] $PAR  To find the work, we slice the water horizontally.  Each slice is a rectangular slab with thickness \(\Delta h\), length $len ft, and width \(s\), as above.  Thus, at height \(h\), the volume of a slice is \(V_{sl} \approx $len ($woh h) \Delta h \hbox{ ft}^3\). $PAR The distance to lift the slice at height  \(h\) is \($hei -  h\), so if \(\delta\) is the density of water, we have that the work to lift one slice, \(\Delta W\), is  \[ \Delta W =    \hbox{Volume} \cdot \delta\cdot \hbox{Distance lifted}   \approx \delta ($len ($woh h) \Delta h) ($hei - h)\hbox{ ft-lb.} \] To find the total work, \(W\), we integrate the work to lift a slice from \(h = 0\) to \(h = $hei\), using \(\delta=62.4 \hbox{ lb/ft}^3\). \[ W = \int_0^{$hei} \delta $len \left($woh h\right)($hei - h)\, dh =    $c \delta \int_0^{$hei} ($hei h - h^2) dh  \]

You are flying in an open plane at an altitude of $h feet and you drop a Coca Cola bottle out of the window.  The bottle will hit the ground after \{ ans_rule(10) \} seconds. (Note: this problem is a bit unrealistic since it ignores air drag.  The scenario described here provides the opening scene in the movie "The Gods must be crazy.")   EOT   ANS(num_cmp($t));   TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  Hint: Study the page on  \{htmlLink("http://www.math.utah.edu/online/1010/gravity", "throwing rocks.")\} EOT    SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD When the bottle hits the ground its height is zero. When the pilot drops the bottle out of the plane its vertical velocity is zero. We set \(h\) to zero in the  \{htmlLink("http://www.math.utah.edu/online/1010/gravity", "formula for height:")\} \(0 = $h - 16t^2.\) Thus \(t = \sqrt{\frac{$h}{16}} = $t\) seconds.

question_text: Solve the separable differential equation  \[  $a x - $b y \sqrt{x^2 + 1} \; \frac{dy}{dx} = 0. \] Subject to the initial condition: \( y(0) = $k \).  \(y =\) \{ ans_rule(40) \}. END_TEXT  $a2 = $a/2; $k2 = $k*$k; $const = $k2 - $d;  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOF')); $SOL  First separate the variables:  \(\displaystyle $a x = $b y \sqrt{x^2 + 1} \; \frac{dy}{dx} \)  \(\displaystyle \frac{$a x}{\sqrt{x^2+1}} dx = $b y dy \)  Now integrate both sides:  \( \displaystyle \int \frac{$a x}{\sqrt{x^2+1}} \; dx = \int $b y dy \)   On the left hand side, make the substitution \(u=x^2+1\), \(du=2xdx\), \(\frac{1}{2}du = xdx\), then   \( \displaystyle \int \frac{$a x}{\sqrt{x^2+1}} \; dx  = \int \frac{$a2}{\sqrt{u}} \; du = $a2 \frac{\sqrt{u}}{1/2} + C \)   \(\displaystyle = $a \sqrt{u} + C = $a \sqrt{x^2+1} + C \).    Thus we have    \(\displaystyle $a \sqrt{x^2+1} + C = $b2 y^2\)   \(\displaystyle y^2 = \frac{$a}{$b2} \sqrt{x^2+1} + \frac{C}{$b2}\)   \(\displaystyle y^2 = \frac{$a}{$b2} \sqrt{x^2+1} + K\).  \(\displaystyle y = \pm \sqrt{\frac{$a}{$b2} \sqrt{x^2+1} + K}\).   We need \(y(0)=$k\), so we have to use +, and we find \(K\) from    \(\displaystyle $k = \sqrt {\frac{$a}{$b2} \sqrt{0^2+1} + K}\):    \(\displaystyle $k2 = \frac{$a}{$b2} + K\)   \(\displaystyle K = $k2 - \frac{$a}{$b2} = $const\).  $PAR Therefore the solution is  \(\displaystyle y = \sqrt{\frac{$a}{$b2} \sqrt{x^2+1} + $const}\).

question_text: \{ textbook_ref_exact("Rogawski ET 2e", "12.4","5") \}   Calculate the 3x3 determinant: $PAR \( \left| \begin{array}{ccc} $a1 & $a2 & $a3 \\ $b1 & $b2 & $b3 \\ $c1 & $c2 & $c3  \end{array} \right| =\) \{ans_rule()\}  END_TEXT   Context()->normalStrings; ANS(Real($det)->cmp) ; Context()->texStrings;  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR $SOL  Using the definition of 3x3 determinant we get: $PAR \( \left| \begin{array}{ccc} $a1 & $a2 & $a3 \\ $b1 & $b2 & $b3 \\ $c1 & $c2 & $c3  \end{array} \right| = $a1 \left| \begin{array}{ccc}  $b2 & $b3 \\  $c2 & $c3  \end{array} \right| - $a2  \left| \begin{array}{ccc}  $b1 & $b3 \\  $c1 & $c3  \end{array} \right| + $a3  \left| \begin{array}{ccc}  $b1 & $b2 \\  $c1 & $c2  \end{array} \right| = \)  \(= $a1($b2\cdot $c3-$b3\cdot $c2)-$a2($b1\cdot $c3-$b3\cdot $c1)+$a3($b1\cdot $c2-$b2\cdot $c1)=$det \)

Use implicit differentiation to find the points where the $BBOLD circle $EBOLD defined by \[ $f = $d \] has horizontal and vertical tangent lines.   The circle has horizontal tangent lines at the \{ helpLink(point, "point(s)") \} \{ ans_rule(15) \}.   The circle has vertical tangent lines at the point(s) \{ ans_rule(15) \}. END_TEXT Context()->normalStrings;  #####################################################################  ANS($ans1->cmp()); ANS($ans2->cmp());  $c2 = $c**2;  Context()->texStrings; BEGIN_SOLUTION By completing squares, the equation of the circle can be written as \[ (x - $a)^2 + (y - $b)^2 = $c2. \] Then, differentiating implicitly with respect to \( x \), gives \[ 2(x - $a) + 2(y - $b) \, \frac{dy}{dx} = 0, \] or \[ \frac{dy}{dx} = - \frac{x - $a}{y - $b}. \] The tangent line to the circle is horizontal where \( \frac{dy}{dx} = 0 \), i.e., where \( x = $a \), which gives \( (y - $b)^2 = $c2 \), or \( y = $b \pm $c = $an1a, $an1b \). Hence, the tangent line to the circle is horizontal at the points \( $ans1 \).   The tangent line to the circle is vertical where \[ 0 = \frac{dx}{dy} = - \frac{y - $b}{x - $a}, \] i.e., where \( y = $b \), which gives \( (x - $a)^2 = $c2 \), or \( x = $a \pm $c = $an2a, $an2b \). Hence, the tangent line to the circle is vertical at the points \( $ans2 \).

question_text: Find the values of the coefficients \(a\), \(b\) and \(c\) so that the conditions $PAR \[ f(0) = $y1, \quad f'(0) = $y2, \quad \mbox{ and } \quad \ f''(0) = $y3 \] $PAR hold for the function $PAR \[ $dfun. \] $PAR \(a = \)\{ans_rule(5)\}  \(b = \)\{ans_rule(5)\}  \(c = \)\{ans_rule(5)\} END_TEXT Context()->normalStrings;   ########################################################################### # check the answer   ########################################################################### ANS(Compute($x)->cmp()); ANS(Compute($y)->cmp()); ANS(Compute($z)->cmp());   ########################################################################### # solution ########################################################################### Context()->texStrings; $e2 = nicestring([$p,$q,1], ["a","b","c"]); $e3 = nicestring([($p)**2, (($q)**2), 2*$q], ["a","b","c"]); $dfa = nicestring([$x, $y, $z],["e^{$p1}", "e^{$p2}", "xe^{$p2}"]); BEGIN_SOLUTION ${BBOLD}SOLUTION:${EBOLD}  Using \(f(0) = $y1\), we obtain \($y1 = a + b\). Using \(f'(0) = $y2\) in the derivative \($dd1\) we obtain \($y2 = $e2\). And using \(f''(0) = $y2\) in the second deriative \($dd2\) we obtain \($y3 = $e3\). Using a computer algebra system we solve the system of equations \[ \begin{align*}  a + b &= $y1 \\ $e2 &= $y2 \\ $e3 &= $y3 \end{align*} \] to get \(a = $x\), \(b = $y\), and \(c = $z\). Thus \(f(x) = $dfa\). END_SOLUTION Context()->normalStrings;  COMMENT('Created in 2013.

The solution of the equation \[ \frac{1}{x-$a} = \frac{2}{x+$b} \]  is \(x = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}. EOT  $answer = 2*$a+$b;   ANS(num_cmp($answer));  $a2=2*$a;  TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  Hint: Take reciprocals on both sides. EOT   SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD This is much like the preceding problem. We start by taking the reciprocal on both sides of the equation.  This gives the equivalent equation \[x-$a = \frac{x + $b}{2}.\] Multiplying with \(2\) on both sides gives \[2x-2\times $a = {x + $b}.\] Subtracting \(x\) and adding \(2\times $a = $a2\) on both sides gives \($answer = x. \)

You are visiting your friend Fabio's house. You find that, as a joke, he filled his swimming pool with Kool-Aid, which dissolved perfectly into the water. However, now that you want to swim, you must remove all of the Kool-Aid contaminated water.  The swimming pool is round, with a $r foot radius. It is $h feet tall and has $d feet of water in it.  How much work is required to remove all of the water by pumping it over the side?  Use the physical definition of work, and the fact that the density of the Kool-Aid contaminated water is \( \sigma = $w lbs/ft^3 \) Don't forget to enter the correct \{ helpLink('units') \}.  (You may enter ${BITALIC}lbf${EITALIC} or ${BITALIC}lb*ft${EITALIC} for ${BITALIC}ft-lb${EITALIC}.)   \{ans_rule(45)\}  END_TEXT  &HINT(EV3(<<'EOT')); $HINT  The formula for work is:   \[\int_{a}^{b} Force * distance \]   Where distance is the distance over which the force is exerted. EOT  &SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOF')); $SOL  Consider a horizontal cross-section of the pool, with thickness \(dx\) if we consider the x-axis to be vertical, in the center of the pool. This is just a very short cylinder, so its volume is:   \( dV = \pi r^2 dx \).   We know r, the radius of the pool, is a constant, \(r= $r\). Now that we have the volume of an arbitrary cross-section of the water, we need to find the force which is exerted on the volume. That force is nothing more than the weight. The constant \( \sigma \) gives us weight-per-volume of the liquid. Therefore, by multipling the volume of the slice by \( \sigma \), we find:   \( dF = \sigma \pi r^2 dx \)   Since Work (W) is given by:   \( W = Fx = F\int_{a}^{b}xdx \)   in the case of a constant force F, all that remains is to find an expression for \( D\), the distance each slice of water is lifted. If we consider the top of the pool as x=0, $h-$d is the distance to the surface of the water, since the height of the pool is $h, and the depth is $d. So we have the distance x from x=$h-$d until x=$h. This results in the integral:   \[ W = \int_{$h-$d}^{$h} \sigma \pi r^2 xdx \]   which is simple to evaluate.

Round your answer to two decimal places.  $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE Slope = \{ ans_rule(10) \} (a value rounded to two decimal places)   END_TEXT  ANS(fun_cmp( "(sin(a+h)-sin(a))/h", vars=>['a','h'] ) ); ANS(num_cmp( $ans , tol=>'0.01' ));   SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));  $SPACE   $BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD   a)  The coordinate of the point \( S \) are \( (x_0,y_0) = ( a, \sin{(a)} ) \) while the coordinates of the point \( T \) are \( (x_1,y_1) = ( a+h, \sin{(a+h)} ) \). In this problem we work out step-by-step the number of group homomorphisms from a dihedral group to a finite cyclic group. Recall that the dihedral group \( \{ dihedral( $n ) \} \) is generated by an element \(a\)  of order \($n\), and an element \(b\) of order 2, satisfying the relation    \((\ast)\)   \( \) \( \) \( \) \( \)   \( \) \( \) \( \) \( \)      \(ba = a^{$n-1}b\)    Let \(f: \{ dihedral( $n ) \} \rightarrow \{ cyclic( $m ) \} \)  be a group homomorphism.    Since \(a^{$n} = e\), properties of homomorphisms then imply that    \($n f(a) \equiv f(a^{$n}) \) (remember that \( \{ cyclic( $m ) \} \) is an additive group)  \(\phantom{$n f(a)} \equiv f(e) \)  \(\phantom{$n f(a)} \equiv 0 \pmod{$m} \)     That means the possible choices for \(f(a)\) are \{ans_rule(20)\} (please answer here as a comma-separated list of integers \(\ge 0\) and \(<$m\)).    Similarly, from \(b^2 = e\) we see that the possible choices for \(f(b)\) are \{ans_rule(20)\} (please answer here as a comma-separated list).    But there is an additional restriction: the group elements \(a, b\) in \( \{ dihedral( $n ) \} \) satisfy the  relation \(ba = a^{$n-1}b\). Apply the group homomorphism \(f\) and use the fact that \( \{ cyclic( $m ) \} \) is Abelian, we see that this implies \( ($n - 2) f(a)=0\). All together, we see that the number of group homomorphisms \(f: \{ dihedral( $n ) \} \rightarrow \{ cyclic( $m ) \} \) is \{ans_rule(20)\}.

question_text: The smallest positive number for which \[\sin(2x)-\sin x = 0 \] is \(x=\)  \{ans_rule(12) \}. EOT ANS(num_cmp(acos(1/2)));  TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Hint:$EBOLD Apply a multiple angle or difference to product rule. EOT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));   $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD Applying the formula \[\sin(2x) = 2\sin x \cos x\] gives \[ \begin{array}{rcl} \sin(2x) - \sin x &= & 2\sin x \cos x - \sin x \\ \\  &=& \sin x(2\cos x - 1) \\ \\ & = & 0 \\  \end{array} \]  Thus \(\sin x = 0 \) or \(\cos x = \frac{1}{2}\).  The smallest positive solution of these equations is \[x= \arccos \frac{1}{2} \approx 1.0472.\]

Fuzzy Logic is used in artificial  intelligence. In fuzzy logic, a proposition has a truth value that is a  number between 0 and 1 inclusive. A proposition with a truth value of 0  is false and one with truth value of 1 is true. Truth values that are between 0 and 1 indicate varying degrees of truth. For instance, the truth value \{ $a \} can be assigned to the statement "Fred is happy."  since Fred is happy most of the time, and the truth value \{ $b \} can be assigned to the statement "John is happy." since John is happy slightly less than half the time.  $PAR The truth value of the negation of a proposition in fuzzy logic is  1 minus the truth value of the proposition. The truth value of a conjunction of two propositions in fuzzy logic is the minimum of the truth values of the two propositions. For example, consider the statement $BITALIC all natural numbers are real numbers.$EITALIC (This is a true statement, but this is actually not important for this discussion.)  This statement can be put as an implication: $BITALIC if \(x\) is a natural number, then \(x\) is a real number. $EITALIC  The  $BBOLD converse$EBOLD of this statement is $BITALIC all real numbers are natural numbers$EITALIC, or $BITALIC if \(x\) is a real number then it is a natural number$EITALIC,  (which is a false statement), the $BBOLD contrapositive$EBOLD is $BITALIC  if \(x\) is not a real number then it isn't a natural number $EITALIC (which is a true  statement), and the $BBOLD negation$EBOLD of the statement is $BITALIC some natural  numbers are not real numbers $EITALIC (which is a false statement). question_text: If \( \displaystyle f(x) =  \int_x^{x^2} t^2dt \) $PAR then  \( f'(x) = \) \{ans_rule(20)\}  \( f'($x1) = \) \{ans_rule(20)\} $PAR EOT  $ans1="2*x*x^4 -  x^2"; $ans2=2*$x1*$x1**4 -  $x1**2;  ANS(fun_cmp($ans1)); ANS(num_cmp($ans2));  &SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT')); Solving this question involves two steps.  The last step is to apply the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus.  So the first step needs to be rewriting the integral so that we can apply this theorem.  So, rewriting, we get the following: \[   f(x) = \int_x^{x^2} t^2dt = \int_0^{x^2} t^2dt - \int_0^x t^2dt \] Now, to find \( f'(x) \), we find the derivative of these two pieces independently.  Remember when taking the derivative of the first term that since the integral is from 0 to \( x^2 \), we will need to  apply the chain rule.  This gives: \[   f'(x) = (x^2)^2(2x) - x^2 = 2x^5 - x^2 \] Finally, to find the answer to the last part, we plug $x1 into the  above formula to get: \[   f'($x1) = 2($x1)^5 - ($x1)^2 = $ans2 \]

question_text: \{ textbook_ref_exact("Rogawski ET 2e", "14.7","21") \} $PAR Find the critical point of the function \(f(x,y)=$f\). $PAR \(c=\) \{ans_rule()\}  Use the Second Derivative Test to determine whether it is \{$mc -> print_a\} $PAR  END_TEXT   Context()->normalStrings; Context("Point"); ANS(Point(Real($x0),Real($y0))->cmp); Context("Numeric"); ANS(str_cmp($mc->correct_ans)); Context()->texStrings;  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR $SOL  First, we find the critical point. We set the first-order partial derivatives of \(f(x,y)=$f\) equal to zero and solve \[f_x(x,y)=$fx=0\] \[f_y(x,y)=$fy=0\] The first equation implies that \(\frac{1}{x+y}=$a\). Substituting into the second equation gives  \[$f2=0 \quad \Rightarrow \quad y=$y0\] We substitute \(y=$y0\) in the first equation and solve for \(x\): \[$a-\frac{1}{x+$y0}=0 \quad \Rightarrow \quad x+$y0=\frac{1}{$a} \quad \Rightarrow \quad x=\frac{-$y0 \cdot $a + 1}{$a}=$x \] We obtain critical point \(\left($x, $y0\right)\).  Notice, that although \(f_x\) and \(f_y\) do not exist where \(x+y=0\), these are not critical points, since \(f\) is not defined at these points. $PAR Now we compute the Discriminant. We find the second-order partials: \[f_{xx}(x,y)=\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left($fx\right)=$fxx\]  \[f_{yy}(x,y)=\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\left($fy\right)=$fyy\]  \[f_{xy}(x,y)=\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\left($fx\right)=$fxy\]  The discriminant is thus \[D(x,y)=f_{xx}f_{yy}-f_{xy}^2=$fxx \cdot \left($fyy\right)-\frac{1}{(x+y)^4}=$disc\] $PAR Applying the Second Derivative Test we have \[D\left($x,$y0\right)=$d0<0\] We conclude that \(f\left($x,$y0\right)\) is a saddle point.

question_text: One's complement representations of integers are used to simplify computer  arithmetic. To represent positive and negative integers with absolute value less than \( 2^{n-1} \), a total of \( n \) bits is used.  The leftmost bit is used to represent the sign: this bit is 0 for  positive integers and 1 for negative integers.   For positive integers, the remaining bits are identical to  the binary representation of the integer. Thus using 4 bits, the  One's complement representation of 5 is 0101.   For negative integers, the remaining bits are found by first  finding the binary representation of the absolute value of the integer  and then taking the complement of each of these bits in the binary  representation. (Thus 1's and 0's get switched)   Thus for example using 4 bits, the One's complement representation of  -5 is 1010, where the initial 1 is to indicate the sign, and the subsequent 010 is the complement of 101 the binary representation of 5.   Find the One's Complement representations, using bit strings of length six, of the following integers. END_TEXT ################################### # Main text BEGIN_TEXT Evaluate the indefinite integral. \[ \int \frac{ dx}{x^2\sqrt{$a2 + x^2}} \] \{ans_rule( 50) \} END_TEXT $ans = $funct; ANS( $funct->cmp() ); #ANS(fun_cmp($ans, limits=>[$lend,$rend], mode=>"antider", vars=>"x")); ################################## Context()->texStrings; ################################### TEXT($PAR, $BBOLD, $BITALIC, "Hi $studentLogin, If you don't get this in 5 tries I'll give you a hint with an applet to help you out.", $EITALIC, $EBOLD, $PAR); $im = image( "trigsub.png", width=>486, height=>306, tex_size=>900 ); $showHint=5; Context()->normalStrings; TEXT(hint( $PAR, MODES(TeX=>'object code', HTML=>$applet->insertAll( debug =>0, reinitialize_button => 0, includeAnswerBox=>0, ), TeX=>$im),"Follow the step-by-step questions in the hint in the online version of this problem." )); ################################## Context()->normalStrings; ################################## Context()->texStrings; SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $BBOLD Solution: $EBOLD $PAR To evaluate this integral use a trigonometric substitution. For this problem use the \(\tan\) substitution. \[x = {$a}\tan(\theta)\] Before proceeding note that \(\tan\theta=\frac{x}{$a}\), and \(\sec\theta=\frac{\sqrt{$a2+x^2}}{$a}\). To see this, label a right triangle so that the tangent is \(x/$a\). We will have the opposite side with length \(x\), and the adjacent side with length \($a\), so the hypotenuse has length \(\sqrt{$a2+x^2}\). With the substitution \[x = {$a}\tan(\theta)\] \[dx = {$a}\sec^2(\theta) \; d\theta\] Therefore: \[\int \frac{ dx}{x^2\sqrt{$a2 + x^2}}= \int \frac{{$a}\sec^2\theta }{{$a2}\tan^2\theta\sqrt{$a2 + $a2\tan^2\theta}}\;d\theta\] \[= \int \frac{{$a}\sec^2\theta }{{$a3}\tan^2\theta\sec\theta}\;d\theta\] \[= \int \frac{\sec\theta }{{$a2}\tan^2\theta}\;d\theta\] \[= \int \frac{\cos\theta }{{$a2}\sin^2\theta}\;d\theta\] We have an odd power of the cosine, so we use a sine substitution. Let \(u=\sin\theta\), then \(du=\cos\theta d\theta\). \[ \int \frac{\cos\theta }{{$a2}\sin^2\theta}\;d\theta =\int \frac{du }{{$a2}u^2}\] \[=-\frac{1}{{$a2}u}+C \] \[=-\frac{1}{{$a2}\sin\theta}+C \]

The purpose of this question is to show you the syntax needed to enter  matrices in WeBWorK when there is only one answer box for entering a matrix  (which is not obvious)  or when there are multiple answer boxes for entering a matrix (which is obvious). The examples below should be self-explanatory, so you can jump to them if you want; however, a detailed explanation follows if you want to read more.   Matrices use square brackets to enclose items in lists.   A matrix with one row, such as a row vector, is a comma separated list enclosed by square brackets. A matrix with more than one row or a column vector is a comma separated list of lists, where each list  uses square brackets to enclose its items. Your answers must use square brackets to enclose each row in a matrix or in a column vector.  Also, a pair of square brackets is needed to enclose a matrix with more than one row (e.g., a \( 2 \times 3 \) matrix and a \( 2 \times 1 \) column vector have multiple rows so they need extra  square brackets, but a \( 1 \times 3 \) row vector has only one row so it does not need extra square brackets).
