If \[ f(x) = \frac{$a x^{$n}}{1-x} \] then \(f^{($n)}(x) = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}.  Note:  There is a way of doing this problem without using the quotient rule $n times. EOT  $ans = "$a * $f_n * (1-x)**(-1-$n)";  ANS(fun_cmp($ans));  $m=$n+1;  $b = $a*$f_n; SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));   $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD You can avoid a repeated  application of the quotient or product rule by using the fact that \[\frac{x^4}{1-x} = -x^3-x^2-x-1+\frac{1}{1-x}.\] (This can be seen, for example, by synthetic division,  or by simply writing the right hand side of this equation  over the common denominator \(1-x\).)  The fourth derivative of \(-x^3-x^2-x-1\) is zero and so \[\begin{array}{rcl} D_x^4 \frac{x^4}{1-x} &=& D_x^4 \frac{1}{1-x} \\  &=& D_x^4 (1-x)^{-1} \\ &=& D_x^3 (1-x)^{-2} \\ &=& 2 D_x^2 (1-x)^{-3} \\ &=& 6 D_x (1-x)^{-4} \\ &=& 24 (1-x)^{-5} \\ \end{array} \]  Thus \[f^{($n)}(x) = \frac{$b}{(1-x)^{$m}} \]

latex_expressions: ['\\(V\\)', '\\($d \\text{m}\\)', '\\($h \\text{m}\\)', '\\(V\\)', '\\($err %\\)', '\\(V\\)', '\\(%\\)', '\\(d\\)', '\\(h\\)', '\\((d,h)=($d,$h)\\)', '\\(d\\)', '\\(h\\)', '\\($err %\\)', '\\(V\\)', '\\($errv\\)', '\\[V=\\pi\\left(\\frac{d}{2}\\right)^2h=\\frac{\\pi}{4}d^2h\\]', '\\[\\Delta V \\approx \\frac{\\partial{V}}{\\partial{d}}\\Delta d + \\frac{\\partial{V}}{\\partial{h}}\\Delta h\\]', '\\[ \\left. \\begin{array}{lcl} \\frac{\\partial{V}}{\\partial{d}}(d,h)=\\frac{\\pi}{2}hd & & \\frac{\\partial{V}}{\\partial{d}}($d,$h)\\approx $dvdd \\\\ & \\Rightarrow & \\\\ \\frac{\\partial{V}}{\\partial{h}}(d,h)=\\frac{\\pi}{4}d^2 & & \\frac{\\partial{V}}{\\partial{h}}($d,$h)\\approx $dvdh   \\end{array} \\right. \\]', '\\[\\Delta V \\approx $dvdd \\Delta d + $dvdh \\Delta h\\]', '\\[ \\left. \\begin{array}{lcl} \\frac{\\Delta d}{$d}=$err1 & \\Rightarrow & \\Delta d=$dd\\\\  \\frac{\\Delta h}{$h}=$err1 & \\Rightarrow & \\Delta h=$dh  \\end{array} \\right. \\]', '\\[\\Delta V \\approx $dvdd\\cdot $dd+$dvdh\\cdot $dh\\approx $errv\\]', '\\[\\frac{\\Delta V}{V}\\cdot 100%=\\frac{$errv \\cdot 100}{\\frac{\\pi}{4} \\cdot $d^2 \\cdot $h}=$percerr %\\]']
question_text: \{ textbook_ref_exact("Rogawski ET 2e", "14.4","39") \} $PAR The volume \(V\) of a cylinder is computed using the values \($d \text{m}\) for the diameter and \($h \text{m}\) for the height. Use the linear approximation to estimate the maximum error in \(V\) if each of these values has a possible error of at most \($err %\). $PAR Percentage error in \(V\):\{ans_rule()\}\(%\)  END_TEXT   Context()->normalStrings; ANS($percerr->cmp); Context()->texStrings;  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR $SOL  We denote by \(d\) and \(h\) the diameter and height of the cylinder, respectively. By the formula of the Volume of a Cylinder we have \[V=\pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^2h=\frac{\pi}{4}d^2h\] The linear approximation is  \[\Delta V \approx \frac{\partial{V}}{\partial{d}}\Delta d + \frac{\partial{V}}{\partial{h}}\Delta h\]  We compute the partial derivatives at \((d,h)=($d,$h)\): \[ \left. \begin{array}{lcl} \frac{\partial{V}}{\partial{d}}(d,h)=\frac{\pi}{2}hd & & \frac{\partial{V}}{\partial{d}}($d,$h)\approx $dvdd \\ & \Rightarrow & \\ \frac{\partial{V}}{\partial{h}}(d,h)=\frac{\pi}{4}d^2 & & \frac{\partial{V}}{\partial{h}}($d,$h)\approx $dvdh   \end{array} \right. \] Hence, \[\Delta V \approx $dvdd \Delta d + $dvdh \Delta h\] We are given that the errors in the measurements of \(d\) and \(h\) are at most \($err %\). Hence,  \[ \left. \begin{array}{lcl} \frac{\Delta d}{$d}=$err1 & \Rightarrow & \Delta d=$dd\\  \frac{\Delta h}{$h}=$err1 & \Rightarrow & \Delta h=$dh  \end{array} \right. \] Substituting we obtain \[\Delta V \approx $dvdd\cdot $dd+$dvdh\cdot $dh\approx $errv\] The error in \(V\) is approximately \($errv\) meters. The percentage error is at most \[\frac{\Delta V}{V}\cdot 100%=\frac{$errv \cdot 100}{\frac{\pi}{4} \cdot $d^2 \cdot $h}=$percerr %\]

\{ beginproblem() \} \{ textbook_ref_exact("Rogawski ET 2e", "15.4","49") \} $PAR Evaluate the triple integral of \(f(x,y,z)=z(x^2+y^2+z^2)^{-3/2}\) over the part of the ball \(x^2+y^2+z^2\le $r2\) defined by \( z\ge \{$r/2\}\). $PAR \($IIINT _{$w} f( x,y,z ) \,dV =\) \{ans_rule()\} $PAR  END_TEXT  ANS($answer->cmp);  Context()->texStrings;  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION')); $PAR $SOL  \{image("image_15_4_59_a.png", width=>211, height=>191)\} $PAR The equation of the sphere in spherical coordinates is \({\rho }^2=$r2\) or \(\rho =$r\).$PAR \{image("image_15_4_59_b.png", width=>220, height=>218)\} \(\rho_0=$r\) $PAR  We write the equation of the plane \(z=\{$r/2\}\) in spherical coordinates: \[ \rho \cos \phi =\{$r/2\}\quad\Rightarrow\quad \rho =\frac{\{$r/2\}}{ \cos \phi } \] To compute the interval of \(\phi\), we must find the value of \(\phi\) corresponding to \(\rho =$r\) on the plane \(z=\{$r/2\}\). For example, the domain of the function  \(g(x) = x^2 \) is \((-\infty,\infty)\).  Enter it in these four answer fields:   \{ ans_rule(3) \} EOT ANS(str_cmp("("));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \{ ans_rule(18) \}, EOT ANS(str_cmp("-infinity"));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \{ ans_rule(18) \} EOT ANS(str_cmp("infinity"));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \{ ans_rule(3) \}.   EOT ANS(str_cmp(")"));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));   The $BITALIC range$EITALIC  of \(g\) is \([0,\infty)\). Enter it here:   \{ ans_rule(3) \} EOT ANS(str_cmp("["));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \{ ans_rule(18) \}, EOT ANS(num_cmp(0));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \{ ans_rule(18) \} EOT ANS(str_cmp("infinity"));  TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));  \{ ans_rule(3) \}.

Consider the function \( f(t) =  $a1 \sec ^2(t) - $b1 t^ { $n1 }  \). Let \( F(t) \) be the antiderivative of \( f(t) \) with \( F(0) = 0 \).   Find \( F(t) \).  Answer:  \{ans_rule(40) \} END_TEXT  $n2=$n1+1; $b2=$b1/$n2; $antideriv ="$a1 * tan(t) - $b2*t^$n2";  ANS(fun_cmp($antideriv, var=>'t', mode=>'antider'));  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOF')); $SOL   Recall that for a term of the form \( Ax^n \) the antiderivative is just the term whose derivative is \( Ax^n \).  That is,  \(\frac{A}{n+1}x^{n+1} + C \) where \( C \) is an unknown constant.  Also, recall that the antiderivative of the \( \sec^2 \) function is the \( \tan \)  function.  Applying these rules term-by-term to our function, we get:   \[F(t) = $a1\tan{t} - \frac{$b1}{\{$n1+1\}}t^{\{$n1+1\}} + C\] \[\quad = $a1\tan{t} - \{$b1/($n1+1)\}t^{\{$n1+1\}} + C \]    Where \( C \) is an artibrary constant.  We are further told that \( F(0) = 0 \) so plugging this into the above general antiderivative, we get:   \[ F(0) = $a1\tan{0} - \{$b1/($n1+1)\}(0)^{\{$n1+1\}} + C = 0 \]     So that the specific antiderivative is: \[   F(t) = $a1\tan{t} - \{$b1/($n1+1)\}t^{\{$n1+1\}} \]

One pipe can fill a tank three times as fast as another pipe. If together the two pipes can fill the tank in 36 minutes, how many minutes would it take the slower pipe to fill the tank by itself?    Your answer:  \{ ans_rule(20) \}.    EOT  $answer = 144; ANS(num_cmp($answer, mode=>"arith"));  TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));  $BBOLD Hint:$EBOLD Introduce a variable. Then set up an equation by asking how much those pipes can do in a minute. EOT  SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));   $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD  Let's suppose it takes the slower pipe \(x\) minutes to fill the tank. Then the slow pipe can fill \(\frac{1}{x}\) of the tank in one minute, the fast pipe can fill \(\frac{3}{x}\) of the tank in one minute, and the two pipes together can fill \(\frac{1}{36}\) of the tank in one minute.     Thus  \[\frac{1}{x}+ \frac{3}{x} = \frac{1}{36}.\] Multiplying with \(36x\) on both sides gives \[36 + 108 = 144 = x.\] The slow pipe will take 144 minutes to fill the tank.
